g0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 24.799-24.800'),(8413,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 24.801'),(8414,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 24.801-24.803'),(8415,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 24.804'),(8416,' Tell me, O Muse, of the man of many devices, who wandered full many ways after he had sacked the sacred citadel of Troy.'),(8417,' Many were the men whose cities he saw and whose mind he learned, aye, and many the woes he suffered in his heart upon the sea,  seeking to win his own life and the return of his comrades.'),(8418,'Yet even so he saved not his comrades, though he desired it sore,'),(8419,' for through their own blind folly they perished—fools, who devoured the kine of Helios Hyperion;'),(8420,'but he took from them the day of their returning.'),(8421,'  Of these things, goddess, daughter of Zeus, beginning where thou wilt, tell thou even unto us.'),(8422,'Now all the rest, as many as had escaped sheer destruction, were at home, safe from both war and sea,'),(8423,'but Odysseus alone, filled with longing for his return and for his wife, did the queenly nymph Calypso, that bright goddess,  keep back in her hollow caves, yearning that he should be her husband.'),(8424,'But when, as the seasons revolved, the year came in which the gods had ordained that he should return home to Ithaca, not even there was he free from toils, even among his own folk.'),(8425,' And all the gods pitied him  save Poseidon; '),(8426,'but he continued to rage unceasingly against godlike Odysseus until at length he reached his own land.'),(8427,'Howbeit Poseidon had gone among the far-off Ethiopians—the Ethiopians who dwell sundered in twain, the farthermost of men, some where Hyperion sets and some where he rises,  there to receive a hecatomb of bulls and rams,'),(8428,'and there he was taking his joy, sitting at the feast;'),(8429,'but the other gods were gathered together in the halls of Olympian Zeus.'),(8430,'Among them the father of gods and men was first to speak,'),(8431,'for in his heart he thought of noble Aegisthus,  whom far-famed Orestes, Agamemnon\'s son, had slain.'),(8432,'Thinking on him he spoke among the immortals, and said:'),(8433,' “Look you now, how ready mortals are to blame the gods.'),(8434,' It is from us, they say, that evils come, but they even of themselves, through their own blind folly, have sorrows beyond that which is ordained. Even as now Aegisthus, beyond that which was ordained, took to himself the wedded wife of the son of Atreus, and slew him on his return, though well he knew of sheer destruction, seeing that we spake to him before, sending Hermes, the keen-sighted Argeiphontes, that he should neither slay the man nor woo his wife;'),(8435,'  for from Orestes shall come vengeance for the son of Atreus when once he has come to manhood and longs for his own land.'),(8436,' So Hermes spoke, but for all his good intent he prevailed not upon the heart of Aegisthus; '),(8437,'and now he has paid the full price of all.” '),(8438,' \nThen the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(8439,'  “Father of us all, thou son of Cronos, high above all lords, aye, verily that man lies low in a destruction that is his due;'),(8440,' so, too, may any other also be destroyed who does such deeds.'),(8441,' But my heart is torn for wise Odysseus, hapless man, who far from his friends has long been suffering woes  in a sea-girt isle, where is the navel of the sea.'),(8442,'\'Tis a wooded isle, and therein dwells a goddess, daughter of Atlas of baneful mind, who knows the depths of every sea, and himself holds the tall pillars which keep earth and heaven apart.'),(8443,'  His daughter it is that keeps back that wretched, sorrowing man; and ever with soft and wheedling words she beguiles him that he may forget Ithaca.'),(8444,' But Odysseus, in his longing to see were it but the smoke leaping up from his own land, yearns to die.'),(8445,' Yet thy  heart doth not regard it, Olympian.'),(8446,' Did not Odysseus beside the ships of the Argives offer thee sacrifice without stint in the broad land of Troy?'),(8447,' Wherefore then didst thou conceive such wrath against him, O Zeus?\"'),(8448,'Then Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, answered her and said:'),(8449,' “My child, what a word has escaped the barrier of thy teeth?'),(8450,'  How should I, then, forget godlike Odysseus, who is beyond all mortals in wisdom, and beyond all has paid sacrifice to the immortal gods, who hold broad heaven?'),(8451,' Nay, it is Poseidon, the earth-enfolder, who is ever filled with stubborn wrath because of the Cyclops, whom Odysseus blinded of his eye—  even the godlike Polyphemus, whose might is greatest among all the Cyclopes;'),(8452,' and the nymph Thoosa bore him, daughter of Phorcys who rules over the unresting sea; for in the hollow caves she lay with Poseidon.'),(8453,' From that time forth Poseidon, the earth-shaker,  does not indeed slay Odysseus, but makes him a wanderer from his native land.'),(8454,'But come, let us who are here all take thought of his return, that he may come home;'),(8455,' and Poseidon will let go his anger,'),(8456,'for he will in no wise be able, against all the immortal gods and in their despite, to contend alone.” '),(8457,' \n  Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(8458,' “Father of us all, thou son of Cronos, high above all lords, if indeed this is now well pleasing to the blessed gods, that the wise Odysseus should return to his own home, let us send forth Hermes, the messenger, Argeiphontes,  to the isle Ogygia, that with all speed he may declare to the fair-tressed nymph our fixed resolve, even the return of Odysseus of the steadfast heart, that he may come home.'),(8459,' But, as for me, I will go to Ithaca, that I may the more arouse his son, and set courage in his heart  to call to an assembly the long-haired Achaeans, and speak out his word to all the wooers, who are ever slaying his thronging sheep and his sleek kine of shambling gait.'),(8460,' And I will guide him to Sparta and to sandy Pylos, to seek tidings of the return of his dear father, if haply he may hear of it,  that good report may be his among men.”'),(8461,'So she spoke, and bound beneath her feet her beautiful sandals, immortal, golden, which were wont to bear her both over the waters of the sea and over the boundless land swift as the blasts of the wind.'),(8462,' And she took her mighty spear, tipped with sharp bronze,  heavy and huge and strong, wherewith she vanquishes the ranks of men—of warriors, with whom she is wroth, she, the daughter of the mighty sire.'),(8463,' Then she went darting down from the heights of Olympus, and took her stand in the land of Ithaca at the outer gate of Odysseus, on the threshold of the court.'),(8464,' In her hand she held the spear of bronze,  and she was in the likeness of a stranger, Mentes, the leader of the Taphians.'),(8465,' There she found the proud wooers.'),(8466,' They were taking their pleasure at draughts in front of the doors, sitting on the hides of oxen which they themselves had slain;'),(8467,' and of the heralds and busy squires,  some were mixing wine and water for them in bowls, others again were washing the tables with porous sponges and setting them forth, while still others were portioning out meats in abundance.'),(8468,'Her the godlike Telemachus was far the first to see, for he was sitting among the wooers, sad at heart,  seeing in thought his noble father, should he perchance come from somewhere and make a scattering of the wooers in the palace, and himself win honor and rule over his own house.'),(8469,' As he thought of these things, sitting among the wooers, he beheld Athena,'),(8470,' and he went straight to the outer door; for in his heart he counted it shame  that a stranger should stand long at the gates. '),(8471,' So, drawing near, he clasped her right hand, and took from her the spear of bronze; and he spoke, and addressed her with winged words:'),(8472,'“Hail, stranger; in our house thou shalt find entertainment '),(8473,'and then, when thou hast tasted food, thou shalt tell of what thou hast need.” '),(8474,' \n  So saying, he led the way, and Pallas Athena followed.'),(8475,' And when they were within the lofty house, he bore the spear and set it against a tall pillar in a polished spear-rack, where were set many spears besides, even those of Odysseus of the steadfast heart.  Athena herself he led and seated on a chair, spreading a linen cloth beneath—a beautiful chair, richly-wrought,'),(8476,' and below was a footstool for the feet.'),(8477,' Beside it he placed for himself an inlaid seat, apart from the others, the wooers, lest the stranger, vexed by their din, should loathe the meal, seeing that he was in the company of overweening men;  and also that he might ask him about his father that was gone.'),(8478,'Then a handmaid brought water for the hands in a fair pitcher of gold, and poured it over a silver basin for them to wash,'),(8479,' and beside them drew up a polished table.'),(8480,' And the grave housewife brought and set before them bread,  and therewith dainties in abundance, giving freely of her store.'),(8481,'And a carver lifted up and placed before them platters of all manner of meats, and set by them golden goblets,'),(8482,' while a herald ever walked to and fro pouring them wine.'),(8483,'\nThen in came the proud wooers,'),(8484,'and thereafter  sat them down in rows on chairs and high seats. Heralds poured water over their hands, and maid-servants heaped by them bread in baskets, and youths filled the bowls brim full of drink; '),(8485,' and they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them.'),(8486,'  Now after the wooers had put from them the desire of food and drink, their hearts turned to other things, to song and to dance; '),(8487,'for these things are the crown of a feast.'),(8488,' And a herald put the beautiful lyre in the hands of Phemius, who sang perforce among the wooers; '),(8489,' and he struck the chords in prelude to his sweet lay.'),(8490,'But Telemachus spoke to flashing-eyed Athena, holding his head close, that the others might not hear: '),(8491,'“Dear stranger, wilt thou be wroth with me for the word that I shall say?'),(8492,' These men care for things like these, the lyre and song,  full easily, seeing that without atonement they devour the livelihood of another, of a man whose white bones, it may be, rot in the rain as they lie upon the mainland, or the wave rolls them in the sea.'),(8493,' Were they to see him returned to Ithaca, they would all pray to be swifter of foot,  rather than richer in gold and in raiment. '),(8494,' But now he has thus perished by an evil doom, nor for us is there any comfort, no, not though any one of men upon the earth should say that he will come;'),(8495,' gone is the day of his returning.'),(8496,' But come, tell me this, and declare it truly.'),(8497,'Where is thy city and where thy parents?'),(8498,'Where is thy city and where thy parents?'),(8499,' On what manner of ship didst thou come,'),(8500,' and how did sailors bring thee to Ithaca? '),(8501,' Who did they declare themselves to be? '),(8502,' For nowise, methinks, didst thou come hither on foot.'),(8503,'And tell me this also truly, that I may know full well,  whether this is thy first coming hither, or whether thou art indeed a friend of my father\'s house. For many were the men who came to our house as strangers, since he, too, had gone to and fro among men.” '),(8504,' \nThen the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(8505,' “Therefore of a truth will I frankly tell thee all.'),(8506,'  I declare that I am Mentes, the son of wise Anchialus, and I am lord over the oar-loving Taphians.'),(8507,' And now have I put in here, as thou seest, with ship and crew, while sailing over the wine-dark sea to men of strange speech, on my way to Temese for copper; and I bear with me shining iron.'),(8508,'  My ship lies yonder beside the fields away from the city, in the harbor of Rheithron, under woody Neion. '),(8509,' Friends of one another do we declare ourselves to be, even as our fathers were, friends from of old. Nay, if thou wilt, go and ask the old warrior Laertes, who, they say,  comes no more to the city, but afar in the fields suffers woes attended by an aged woman as his handmaid, who sets before him food and drink, after weariness has laid hold of his limbs, as he creeps along the slope of his vineyard plot.'),(8510,' And now am I come,'),(8511,' for of a truth men said that he,  thy father, was among his people; '),(8512,' but lo, the gods are thwarting him of his return. '),(8513,' For not yet has goodly Odysseus perished on the earth, but still, I ween, he lives and is held back on the broad sea in a sea-girt isle, and cruel men keep him, a savage folk, that constrain him, haply sore against his will.'),(8514,'  Nay, I will now prophesy to thee, as the immortals put it in my heart, and as I think it shall be brought to pass, though I am in no wise a soothsayer, nor one versed in the signs of birds.'),(8515,' Not much longer shall he be absent from his dear native land, no, not though bonds of iron hold him.'),(8516,'  He will contrive a way to return, for he is a man of many devices.'),(8517,' But come, tell me this and declare it truly, whether indeed, tall as thou art, thou art the son of Odysseus himself.'),(8518,' Wondrously like his are thy head and beautiful eyes; for full often did we consort with one another  before he embarked for the land of Troy, whither others, too, the bravest of the Argives, went in their hollow ships.'),(8519,' But since that day neither have I seen Odysseus, nor he me.\"'),(8520,'Then wise Telemachus answered her:'),(8521,' “Therefore of a truth, stranger, will I frankly tell thee all.'),(8522,'  My mother says that I am his child; but I know not, '),(8523,' for never yet did any man of himself know his own parentage.'),(8524,' Ah, would that I had been the son of some blest man, whom old age overtook among his own possessions.'),(8525,' But now of him who was the most ill-fated of mortal men  they say that I am sprung, since thou askest me of this.”'),(8526,'Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(8527,' “Surely, then, no nameless lineage have the gods appointed for thee in time to come, seeing that Penelope bore thee such as thou art.'),(8528,' But come, tell me this and declare it truly.'),(8529,' What need hast thou of it?'),(8530,' What need hast thou of it?'),(8531,' For this plainly is no meal to which each brings his portion, '),(8532,' For this plainly is no meal to which each brings his portion, '),(8533,' with such outrage and overweening do they seem to me to be feasting in thy halls.'),(8534,' Angered would a man be at seeing all these shameful acts, any man of sense who should come among them.” '),(8535,' \n  Then wise Telemachus answered her:'),(8536,' “Stranger, since indeed thou dost ask and question me of this, our house once bade fair to be rich and honorable, so long as that man was still among his people.'),(8537,' But now the gods have willed otherwise in their evil devising,  seeing that they have caused him to pass from sight as they have no other man. For I should not so grieve for his death, if he had been slain among his comrades in the land of the Trojans, or had died in the arms of his friends, when he had wound up the skein of war.'),(8538,' Then would the whole host of the Achaeans have made him a tomb,  and for his son, too, he would have won great glory in days to come.'),(8539,' But as it is, the spirits of the storm have swept him away and left no tidings:'),(8540,' he is gone out of sight, out of hearing, and for me he has left anguish and weeping;'),(8541,' nor do I in any wise mourn and wail for him alone, seeing that the gods have brought upon me other sore troubles.'),(8542,'  For all the princes who hold sway over the islands—Dulichium and Same and wooded Zacynthus—and those who lord it over rocky Ithaca, all these woo my mother and lay waste my house.'),(8543,' And she neither refuses the hateful marriage,  nor is she able to make an end;'),(8544,' but they with feasting consume my substance:'),(8545,' ere long they will bring me, too, to ruin.\"'),(8546,'Then, stirred to anger, Pallas Athena spoke to him:'),(8547,' “Out on it! Thou hast of a truth sore need of Odysseus that is gone, that he might put forth his hands upon the shameless wooers.'),(8548,'  Would that he might come now and take his stand at the outer gate of the house, with helmet and shield and two spears, such a man as he was when I first saw him in our house drinking and making merry, on his way back from Ephyre, from the house of Ilus, son of Mermerus.  For thither, too, went Odysseus in his swift ship in search of a deadly drug, that he might have wherewith to smear his bronze-tipped arrows; '),(8549,' yet Ilus gave it not to him, for he stood in awe of the gods that are forever; but my father gave it, '),(8550,' for he held him strangely dear. Would, I say, that in such strength Odysseus might come amongst the wooers;'),(8551,' then should they all find swift destruction and bitterness in their wooing.'),(8552,' Yet these things verily lie on the knees of the gods, whether he shall return and wreak vengeance in his halls, or whether he shall not; '),(8553,' but for thyself, I bid thee take thought  how thou mayest thrust forth the wooers from the hall. '),(8554,' Come now, give ear, and hearken to my words.'),(8555,' On the morrow call to an assembly the Achaean lords, and speak out thy word to all, and let the gods be thy witnesses. '),(8556,' As for the wooers, bid them scatter, each to his own;  and for thy mother, if her heart bids her marry, let her go back to the hall of her mighty father, '),(8557,' and there they will prepare a wedding feast, and make ready the gifts full many—aye, all that should follow after a well-loved daughter.'),(8558,' And to thyself will I give wise counsel, if thou wilt hearken. '),(8559,'   Man with twenty rowers the best ship thou hast, and go to seek tidings of thy father, that has long been gone, if haply any mortal may tell thee, or thou mayest hear a voice from Zeus, which oftenest brings tidings to men.'),(8560,' First go to Pylos and question goodly Nestor,  and from thence to Sparta to fair-haired Menelaus; '),(8561,' for he was the last to reach home of the brazen-coated Achaeans.'),(8562,' If so be thou shalt hear that thy father is alive and coming home, then verily, though thou art sore afflicted, thou couldst endure for yet a year.'),(8563,' But if thou shalt hear that he is dead and gone,  then return to thy dear native land and heap up a mound for him, and over it pay funeral rites, full many as is due, and give thy mother to a husband. '),(8564,'Then when thou hast done all this and brought it to an end, thereafter take thought in mind and heart  how thou mayest slay the wooers in thy halls whether by guile or openly;'),(8565,' for it beseems thee not to practise childish ways, since thou art no longer of such an age.'),(8566,' Or hast thou not heard what fame the goodly Orestes won among all mankind when he slew his father\'s murderer,  the guileful Aegisthus, for that he slew his glorious father?'),(8567,' Thou too, my friend, for I see that thou art comely and tall, be thou valiant, that many an one of men yet to be born may praise thee.'),(8568,' But now I will go down to my swift ship and my comrades, who, methinks, are chafing much at waiting for me.'),(8569,'  For thyself, give heed and have regard to my words.”'),(8570,'Then wise Telemachus answered her: '),(8571,' “Stranger, in truth thou speakest these things with kindly thought, as a father to his son, and never will I forget them. '),(8572,' But come now, tarry, eager though thou art to be gone,  in order that when thou hast bathed and satisfied thy heart to the full, thou mayest go to thy ship glad in spirit, and bearing a gift costly and very beautiful, which shall be to thee an heirloom from me, even such a gift as dear friends give to friends.\"'),(8573,'Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(8574,' “Stay me now no longer, when I am eager to be gone,'),(8575,' and whatsoever gift thy heart bids thee give me, give it when I come back, to bear to my home, choosing a right beautiful one; '),(8576,' it shall bring thee its worth in return.\"'),(8577,'So spoke the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, and departed,  flying upward as a bird; '),(8578,'and in his heart she put strength and courage, and made him think of his father even more than aforetime.'),(8579,' And in his mind he marked her and marvelled, '),(8580,' for he deemed that she was a god; '),(8581,' and straightway he went among the wooers, a godlike man. '),(8582,' \n  For them the famous minstrel was singing, and they sat in silence listening;'),(8583,' and he sang of the return of the Achaeans—the woeful return from Troy which Pallas Athena laid upon them.'),(8584,' And from her upper chamber the daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope, heard his wondrous song,'),(8585,'  and she went down the high stairway from her chamber, not alone, for two handmaids attended her.'),(8586,' Now when the fair lady had come to the wooers, she stood by the door-post of the well-built hall, holding before her face her shining veil; '),(8587,'  and a faithful handmaid stood on either side of her. '),(8588,' Then she burst into tears, and spoke to the divine minstrel:'),(8589,'\n“Phemius, many other things thou knowest to charm mortals, deeds of men and gods which minstrels make famous.'),(8590,' Sing them one of these, as thou sittest here,  and let them drink their wine in silence. '),(8591,' But cease from this woeful song which ever harrows the heart in my breast, for upon me above all women has come a sorrow not to be forgotten.'),(8592,' So dear a head do I ever remember with longing, even my husband, whose fame is wide through Hellas and mid-Argos.\"'),(8593,'  Then wise Telemachus answered her: '),(8594,' “My mother, why dost thou begrudge the good minstrel to give pleasure in whatever way his heart is moved?'),(8595,' It is not minstrels that are to blame, but Zeus, I ween, is to blame, who gives to men that live by toil, to each one as he will. '),(8596,'  With this man no one can be wroth if he sings of the evil doom of the Danaans; '),(8597,'for men praise that song the most which comes the newest to their ears.'),(8598,' For thyself, let thy heart and soul endure to listen;'),(8599,'for not Odysseus alone lost  in Troy the day of his return, but many others likewise perished.'),(8600,' Nay, go to thy chamber, and busy thyself with thine own tasks, the loom and the distaff, and bid thy handmaids ply their tasks;'),(8601,' but speech shall be for men, for all, but most of all for me; '),(8602,' since mine is the authority in the house.\"'),(8603,' She then, seized with wonder, went back to her chamber,'),(8604,'for she laid to heart the wise saying of her son.'),(8605,' Up to her upper chamber she went with her handmaids, and then bewailed Odysseus, her dear husband until flashing-eyed Athena cast sweet sleep upon her eyelids. '),(8606,' \n  But the wooers broke into uproar throughout the shadowy halls, and all prayed, each that he might lie by her side.'),(8607,' And among them wise Telemachus was the first to speak:'),(8608,'“Wooers of my mother, overweening in your insolence, for the present let us make merry with feasting,  but let there be no brawling; for this is a goodly thing, to listen to a minstrel such as this man is, like to the gods in voice.'),(8609,' But in the morning let us go to the assembly and take our seats, one and all, that I may declare my word to you outright that you depart from these halls.'),(8610,' Prepare you other feasts,  eating your own substance and changing from house to house. '),(8611,' But if this seems in your eyes to be a better and more profitable thing, that one man\'s livelihood should be ruined without atonement, waste ye it.'),(8612,' But I will call upon the gods that are forever, if haply Zeus may grant that deeds of requital may be wrought.'),(8613,'  Without atonement, then, should ye perish within my halls.”'),(8614,'So he spoke, and they all bit their lips and marvelled at Telemachus, for that he spoke boldly.'),(8615,'Then Antinous, son of Eupeithes, answered him:'),(8616,'“Telemachus, verily the gods themselves are teaching thee  to be a man of vaunting tongue, and to speak with boldness.'),(8617,'May the son of Cronos never make thee king in sea-girt Ithaca, which thing is by birth thy heritage.\"'),(8618,' Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(8619,'“Antinous, wilt thou be wroth with me for the word that I shall say?'),(8620,'  Even this should I be glad to accept from the hand of Zeus.'),(8621,' Thinkest thou indeed that this is the worst fate among men?'),(8622,' Nay, it is no bad thing to be a king.'),(8623,' Straightway one\'s house grows rich and oneself is held in greater honor. '),(8624,' However, there are other kings of the Achaeans  full many in seagirt Ithaca, both young and old. One of these haply may have this place, since goodly Odysseus is dead.'),(8625,' But I will be lord of our own house and of the slaves that goodly Odysseus won for me.\"'),(8626,'Then Eurymachus, son of Polybus, answered him:'),(8627,'  “Telemachus, this matter verily lies on the knees of the gods, who of the Achaeans shall be king in sea-girt Ithaca; '),(8628,' but as for thy possessions, thou mayest keep them thyself, and be lord in thine own house.'),(8629,' Never may that man come who by violence and against thy will shall wrest thy possessions from thee, while men yet live in Ithaca.'),(8630,' Where are his kinsmen and his native fields? '),(8631,' Does he bring some tidings of thy father\'s coming, or came he hither in furtherance of some matter of his own?'),(8632,'  How he started up, and was straightway gone! Nor did he wait to be known;'),(8633,' and yet he seemed no base man to look upon.\"'),(8634,' Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(8635,'“Eurymachus, surely my father\'s home-coming is lost and gone.'),(8636,'No longer do I put trust in tidings, whencesoever they may come,  nor reck I of any prophecy which my mother haply may learn of a seer, when she has called him to the hall.'),(8637,' But this stranger is a friend of my father\'s house from Taphos. He declares that he is Mentes, son of wise Anchialus, and he is lord over the oar-loving Taphians.\"'),(8638,'So spoke Telemachus, but in his heart he knew the immortal goddess.'),(8639,'Now the wooers turned to the dance and to gladsome song, and made them merry, and waited till evening should come; '),(8640,' and as they made merry dark evening came upon them.'),(8641,' Then they went, each man to his house, to take their rest.'),(8642,'  But Telemachus, where his chamber was built in the beautiful court, high, in a place of wide outlook, thither went to his bed, pondering many things in mind; '),(8643,' and with him, bearing blazing torches, went true-hearted Eurycleia, daughter of Ops, son of Peisenor.  Her long ago Laertes had bought with his wealth, when she was in her first youth, and gave for her the price of twenty oxen; and he honored her even as he honored his faithful wife in his halls, but he never lay with her in love, for he shunned the wrath of his wife.'),(8644,' She it was who bore for Telemachus the blazing torches;  for she of all the handmaids loved him most, and had nursed him when he was a child. '),(8645,'  He opened the doors of the well-built chamber, sat down on the bed, and took off his soft tunic '),(8646,' and laid it in the wise old woman\'s hands.'),(8647,' And she folded and smoothed the tunic  and hung it on a peg beside the corded bedstead, and then went forth from the chamber, drawing the door to by its silver handle, and driving the bolt home with the thong.'),(8648,' So there, the night through, wrapped in a fleece of wool, he pondered in his mind upon the journey which Athena had shewn him.'),(8649,' Soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, up from his bed arose the dear son of Odysseus and put on his clothing. About his shoulder he slung his sharp sword, and beneath his shining feet bound his fair sandals,  and went forth from his chamber like a god to look upon. '),(8650,' Straightway he bade the clear-voiced heralds to summon to the assembly the long-haired Achaeans.'),(8651,' And the heralds made the summons, and the Achaeans assembled full quickly. '),(8652,' Now when they were assembled and met together,  Telemachus went his way to the place of assembly, holding in his hand a spear of bronze—not alone, for along with him two swift hounds followed;'),(8653,' and wondrous was the grace that Athena shed upon him, '),(8654,' and all the people marvelled at him as he came.'),(8655,' But he sat down in his father\'s seat, and the elders gave place.'),(8656,'\n  Then among them the lord Aegyptius was the first to speak, a man bowed with age and wise with wisdom untold. '),(8657,' Now he spoke, because his dear son had gone in the hollow ships to Ilius, famed for its horses, in the company of godlike Odysseus, even the warrior Antiphus.'),(8658,' But him the savage Cyclops had slain  in his hollow cave, and made of him his latest meal. '),(8659,' Three others there were; one, Eurynomus, consorted with the wooers, and two ever kept their father\'s farm.'),(8660,' Yet, even so, he could not forget that other, mourning and sorrowing; '),(8661,' and weeping for him he addressed the assembly, and spoke among them:'),(8662,'  “Hearken now to me, men of Ithaca, to the word that I shall say.'),(8663,' Never have we held assembly or session since the day when goodly Odysseus departed in the hollow ships.'),(8664,' And now who has called us together? '),(8665,' On whom has such need come either of the young men or of those who are older?'),(8666,'  Has he heard some tidings of the army\'s return, which he might tell us plainly, seeing that he has first learned of it himself? '),(8667,' Or is there some other public matter on which he is to speak and address us? '),(8668,' A good man he seems in my eyes, a blessed man.'),(8669,' May Zeus fulfil unto him himself some good, even whatsoever he desires in his heart.”'),(8670,'  So he spoke, and the dear son of Odysseus rejoiced at the word of omen; nor did he thereafter remain seated, but was fain to speak. So he took his stand in the midst of the assembly,'),(8671,'and the staff was placed in his hands by the herald Peisenor, wise in counsel. '),(8672,' Then he spoke, addressing first the old man:'),(8673,'\n  “Old man, not far off, as thou shalt soon learn thyself, is that man who has called the host together—even I;'),(8674,'for on me above all others has sorrow come. '),(8675,'I have neither heard any tidings of the army\'s return, which I might tell you plainly, seeing that I had first learned of it myself, nor is there any other public matter on which I am to speak and address you.  Nay, it is mine own need, for that evil has fallen upon my house in two-fold wise.'),(8676,'First, I have lost my noble sire who was once king among you here, and was gentle as a father; '),(8677,' and now there is come an evil yet greater far, which will presently altogether destroy my house and ruin all my livelihood.'),(8678,'  My mother have wooers beset against her will, the sons of those men who are here the noblest. They shrink from going to the house of her father, Icarius, that he may himself exact the bride-gifts for his daughter, and give her to whom he will, even to him who meets his favour,'),(8679,' but thronging our house day after day they slay our oxen and sheep and fat goats, and keep revel, and drink the sparkling wine recklessly;'),(8680,' and havoc is made of all this wealth.'),(8681,' For there is no man here, such as Odysseus was, to ward off ruin from the house.'),(8682,'  As for me, I am no-wise such as he to ward it off.'),(8683,' Nay verily, even if I try I shall be found a weakling and one knowing naught of valor.'),(8684,' Yet truly I would defend myself, if I had but the power;'),(8685,' for now deeds past all enduring have been wrought, and past all that is seemly has my house been destroyed. '),(8686,' Take shame upon yourselves,  and have regard to your neighbors who dwell roundabout,'),(8687,' and fear the wrath of the gods, lest haply they turn against you in anger at your evil deeds.'),(8688,' I pray you by Olympian Zeus, and by Themis who looses and gathers the assemblies of men, '),(8689,'  forbear, my friends, and leave me alone to pine in bitter grief—unless indeed my father, goodly Odysseus, despitefully wrought the well-greaved Achaeans woe, in requital whereof ye work me woe despitefully by urging these men on.'),(8690,' For me it were better  that ye should yourselves eat up my treasures and my flocks.'),(8691,' If ye were to devour them, recompense would haply be made some day; '),(8692,' for just so long should we go up and down the city, pressing our suit and asking back our goods, until all was given back.'),(8693,' But now past cure are the woes ye put upon my heart.”'),(8694,'  Thus he spoke in wrath, and dashed the staff down upon the ground, bursting into tears; '),(8695,'and pity fell upon all the people.'),(8696,' Then all the others kept silent, and no man had the heart to answer Telemachus with angry words. '),(8697,' Antinous alone answered him, and said:'),(8698,'\n  “Telemachus, thou braggart, unrestrained in daring, what a thing hast thou said, putting us to shame, '),(8699,'\nand wouldest fain fasten reproach upon us!'),(8700,' Nay, I tell thee, it is not the Achaean wooers who are anywise at fault, but thine own mother, for she is crafty above all women.'),(8701,' For it is now the third year and the fourth will soon pass,  since she has been deceiving the hearts of the Achaeans in their breasts.'),(8702,' To all she offers hopes, and has promises for each man, sending them messages, but her mind is set on other things.'),(8703,' And she devised in her heart this guileful thing also:'),(8704,' she set up in her halls a great web, and fell to weaving—  fine of thread was the web and very wide;'),(8705,'  and straightway she spoke among us:'),(8706,'“‘Young men, my wooers, since goodly Odysseus is dead, be patient, though eager for my marriage, until I finish this robe—I would not that my spinning should come to naught—a shroud for the lord Laertes, against the time when  the fell fate of grievous death shall strike him down; lest any of the Achaean women in the land should be wroth with me,'),(8707,'if he, who had won great possessions, were to lie without a shroud.\'\"'),(8708,'So she spoke, and our proud hearts consented.'),(8709,' Then day by day she would weave at the great web,  but by night would unravel it, when she had let place torches by her.'),(8710,'Thus for three years she by her craft kept the Achaeans from knowing, and beguiled them;'),(8711,'but when the fourth year came as the seasons rolled on, even then one of her women who knew all told us, and we caught her unravelling the splendid web.'),(8712,' So she finished it against her will, perforce.'),(8713,' Therefore to thee the wooers make answer thus, that thou mayest thyself know it in thine heart, and that all the Achaeans may know.'),(8714,' Send away thy mother, and command her to wed whomsoever her father bids, and whoso is pleasing to her.'),(8715,'  But if she shall continue long time to vex the sons of the Achaeans, mindful in her heart of this, that Athena has endowed her above other women with knowledge of fair handiwork and an understanding heart, and wiles, such as we have never yet heard that any even of the women of old knew, of those who long ago were fair-tressed Achaean women—  Tyro and Alcmene and Mycene of the fair crown - '),(8716,' of whom not one was like Penelope in shrewd device;'),(8717,' yet this at least she devised not aright.'),(8718,' For so long shall men devour thy livelihood and thy possessions, even as long as she shall keep the counsel which  the gods now put in her heart.'),(8719,' Great fame she brings on herself, but on thee regret for thy much substance.'),(8720,' For us, we will go neither to our lands nor else whither, until she marries that one of the Achaeans whom she will.” '),(8721,' \nThen wise Telemachus answered him, and said:'),(8722,'  “Antinous, in no wise may I thrust forth from the house against her will her that bore me and reared me; '),(8723,' and, as for my father, he is in some other land, whether he be alive or dead.'),(8724,' An evil thing it were for me to pay back a great price to Icarius, as I must, if of my own will I send my mother away. '),(8725,' For from her father\'s hand shall I suffer evil, and heaven  will send other ills besides, for my mother as she leaves the house will invoke the dread Avengers;'),(8726,' and I shall have blame, too, from men.'),(8727,' Therefore will I never speak this word.'),(8728,' And for you, if your own heart is wroth here at, get you forth from my halls and prepare you other feasts,  eating your own substance and changing from house to house. '),(8729,' But if this seems in your eyes to be a better and more profitable thing, that one man\'s livelihood should be ruined without atonement, waste ye it.'),(8730,' But I will call upon the gods that are forever, if haply Zeus may grant that deeds of requital may be wrought.'),(8731,' Without atonement then should ye perish within my halls.”'),(8732,'So spoke Telemachus, and in answer Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, sent forth two eagles, flying from on high, from a mountain peak.'),(8733,' For a time they flew swift as the blasts of the wind side by side with wings outspread; '),(8734,'  but when they reached the middle of the many-voiced assembly, then they wheeled about, flapping their wings rapidly, and down on the heads of all they looked, and death was in their glare.'),(8735,' Then they tore with their talons one another\'s cheeks and necks on either side, and darted away to the right across the houses and the city of the men.'),(8736,' But they were seized with wonder at the birds when their eyes beheld them,'),(8737,' and pondered in their hearts on what was to come to pass.'),(8738,' Then among them spoke the old lord Halitherses, son of Mastor, '),(8739,'for he surpassed all men of his day in knowledge of birds and in uttering words of fate.'),(8740,'  He with good intent addressed their assembly, and spoke among them:'),(8741,'“Hearken now to me, men of Ithaca, to the word that I shall say; '),(8742,'and to the wooers especially do I declare and announce these things,'),(8743,' since on them a great woe is rolling. '),(8744,' For Odysseus shall not long be away from his friends, but even now, methinks,  he is near, and is sowing death and fate for these men, one and all.'),(8745,' Aye, and to many others of us also who dwell in clear-seen Ithaca will he be a bane.'),(8746,' But long ere that let us take thought how we may make an end of this—'),(8747,' or rather let them of themselves make an end, '),(8748,'for this is straightway the better course for them.'),(8749,' Not as one untried do I prophesy, but with sure knowledge.'),(8750,'  For unto Odysseus I declare that all things are fulfilled even as I told him, when the Argives embarked for Ilios and with them went Odysseus of many wiles. '),(8751,'I declared that after suffering many ills and losing all his comrades he would come home in the twentieth year  unknown to all; '),(8752,'and lo, all this is now being brought to pass.” '),(8753,' \nThen Eurymachus, son of Polybus, answered him, and said:'),(8754,' “Old man, up now, get thee home and prophesy to thy children, lest haply in days to come they suffer ill.'),(8755,' In this matter I am better far than thou to prophesy.'),(8756,' Many birds there are that fare to and fro under the rays of the sun, and not all are fateful.'),(8757,' As for Odysseus, he has perished far away, as I would that thou hadst likewise perished with him. '),(8758,' Then wouldst thou not prate so much in thy reading of signs,  or be urging Telemachus on in his wrath, hoping for some gift for thy house, if haply he shall give it.'),(8759,' But I will speak out to thee, and this word shall verily be brought to pass. '),(8760,' If thou, wise in the wisdom of old, shalt beguile with thy talk a younger man, and set him on to be wroth,  for him in the first place it shall be the more grievous, and he will in no case be able to do aught because of these men here,'),(8761,'and on thee, old man, will we lay a fine which it will grieve thy soul to pay,'),(8762,'and bitter shall be thy sorrow.'),(8763,' And to Telemachus I myself, here among all, will offer this counsel.'),(8764,' His mother let him bid to go back to the house of her father,'),(8765,'  and they will prepare a wedding feast and make ready the gifts full many,—aye, all that should follow after a well-loved daughter. '),(8766,'For ere that, methinks, the sons of the Achaeans will not cease from their grievous wooing, since in any case we fear no man,—  no, not Telemachus for all his many words,—nor do we reck of any soothsaying which thou, old man, mayest declare; it will fail of fulfillment, and thou shalt be hated the more.'),(8767,' Aye, and his possessions shall be devoured in evil wise, nor shall requital ever be made, so long as she shall put off the Achaeans  in the matter of her marriage. '),(8768,' And we on our part waiting here day after day are rivals by reason of her excellence, and go not after other women, whom each one might fitly wed.\"'),(8769,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(8770,'“Eurymachus and all ye other lordly wooers,  in this matter I entreat you no longer nor speak thereof, '),(8771,'for now the gods know it, and all the Achaeans.'),(8772,' But come, give me a swift ship and twenty comrades who will accomplish my journey for me to and fro.'),(8773,'For I shall go to Sparta and to sandy Pylos  to seek tidings of the return of my father that has long been gone, if haply any mortal man may tell me, or I may hear a voice from Zeus, which oftenest brings tidings to men.'),(8774,'  If so be I shall hear that my father is alive and coming home, then verily, though I am sore afflicted, I could endure for yet a year. '),(8775,'But if I shall hear that he is dead and gone, then I will return to my dear native land and heap up a mound for him, and over it pay funeral rites, full many, as is due, and give my mother to a husband.” '),(8776,' \nSo saying he sat down, and among them rose  Mentor, who was a comrade of noble Odysseus. To him, on departing with his ships, Odysseus had given all his house in charge, that it should obey the old man and that he should keep all things safe.'),(8777,' He with good intent addressed their assembly, and spoke among them:'),(8778,'\n“Hearken now to me, men of Ithaca, to the word that I shall say.'),(8779,'  Never henceforth let sceptred king with a ready heart be kind and gentle, nor let him heed righteousness in his heart, but let him ever be harsh and work unrighteousness, '),(8780,' seeing that no one remembers divine Odysseus of the people whose lord he was; yet gentle was he as a father.'),(8781,'  But of a truth I begrudge not the proud wooers that they work deeds of violence in the evil contrivings of their minds, '),(8782,' for it is at the hazard of their own lives that they violently devour the house of Odysseus, who, they say, will no more return. '),(8783,' Nay, rather it is with the rest of the folk that I am wroth, that ye all  sit thus in silence, and utter no word of rebuke to make the wooers cease, though ye are many and they but few.\"'),(8784,'Then Leocritus, son of Euenor, answered him:'),(8785,'“Mentor, thou mischief-maker, thou wanderer in thy wits, what hast thou said, bidding men make us cease?'),(8786,' Nay, it were a hard thing  to fight about a feast with men that moreover outnumber you. '),(8787,'For if Ithacan Odysseus himself were to come and be eager at heart to drive out from his hall the lordly wooers who are feasting in his house, then should his wife have no joy  at his coming, though sorely she longed for him, but right here would he meet a shameful death, if he fought with men that outnumbered him.'),(8788,' Thou hast not spoken aright. '),(8789,' But come now, ye people, scatter, each one of you to his own lands. As for this fellow, Mentor and Halitherses will speed his journey, for they are friends of his father\'s house from of old.'),(8790,'  But methinks he will long abide here and get his tidings in Ithaca, and never accomplish this journey.\"'),(8791,'So he spoke, and hastily broke up the assembly.'),(8792,'They then scattered, each one to his own house; and the wooers went to the house of divine Odysseus.'),(8793,'\n  But Telemachus went apart to the shore of the sea, and having washed his hands in the grey seawater, prayed to Athena:'),(8794,' “Hear me, thou who didst come yesterday as a god to our house, and didst bid me go in a ship over the misty deep to seek tidings of the return of my father, that has long been gone.'),(8795,'  Lo, all this the Achaeans hinder, but the wooers most of all in their evil insolence.” '),(8796,' \nSo he spoke in prayer, and Athena drew near to him in the likeness of Mentor, both in form and invoice; and she spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(8797,'\n  “Telemachus, neither hereafter shalt thou be a base man or a witless, if aught of thy father\'s goodly spirit has been instilled into thee, such a man was he to fulfil both deed and word.'),(8798,' So then shall this journey of thine be neither vain nor unfulfilled.'),(8799,' But if thou art not the son of him and of Penelope,  then I have no hope that thou wilt accomplish thy desire. '),(8800,'Few sons indeed are like their fathers; most are worse, few better than their fathers.'),(8801,' But since neither hereafter shalt thou be a base man or a witless, nor has the wisdom of Odysseus wholly failed thee,  there is therefore hope that thou wilt accomplish this work.'),(8802,' Now then let be the will and counsel of the wooers—fools, for they are in no wise either prudent or just,'),(8803,' nor do they know aught of death or black fate, which verily is near at hand for them, that they shall all perish in a day.'),(8804,' But for thyself, the journey on which thy heart is set shall not be long delayed,'),(8805,'  so true a friend of thy father\'s house am I, who will equip for thee a swift ship, and myself go with thee.'),(8806,' But go thou now to the house and join the company of the wooers; make ready stores, and bestow all in vessels—  wine in jars, and barley meal, the marrow of men, in stout skins;'),(8807,' —but I, going through the town, will quickly gather comrades that go willingly.'),(8808,' And ships there are full many in sea-girt Ithaca, both new and old; '),(8809,' of these will I choose out for thee the one that is best,  and quickly will we make her ready and launch her on the broad deep.\"'),(8810,'So spoke Athena, daughter of Zeus,'),(8811,' nor did Telemachus tarry long after he had heard the voice of the goddess,'),(8812,'but went his way to the house, his heart heavy within him. He found there the proud wooers in the halls,  flaying goats and singeing swine in the court.'),(8813,' And Antinous with a laugh came straight to Telemachus, and clasped his hand, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(8814,'  Nay, I bid thee, eat and drink even as before. All these things the Achaeans will surely provide for thee—the ship and chosen oarsmen—that with speed thou mayest go to sacred Pylos to seek for tidings of thy noble father.” '),(8815,'  Nay, I bid thee, eat and drink even as before. All these things the Achaeans will surely provide for thee—the ship and chosen oarsmen—that with speed thou mayest go to sacred Pylos to seek for tidings of thy noble father.” '),(8816,' \nThen wise Telemachus answered him:'),(8817,'  “Antinous, in no wise is it possible for me in your overweening company to sit at meat quietly and to make merry with an easy mind.'),(8818,' Is it not enough, ye wooers, that in time past ye wasted many goodly possessions of mine, while I was still a child? '),(8819,'But now that I am grown,  and gain knowledge by hearing the words of others, yea and my spirit waxes within me, I will try how I may hurl forth upon your evil fates, either going to Pylos or here in this land.'),(8820,' For go I will, nor shall the journey be in vain whereof I speak, '),(8821,' though I voyage in another\'s ship, since I may not be master of ship or oarsmen.'),(8822,'  So, I ween, it seemed to you to be more to your profit.\"'),(8823,' He spoke, and snatched his hand from the hand of Antinous without more ado,'),(8824,' and the wooers were busy with the feast throughout the hall.'),(8825,' They mocked and jeered at him in their talk;'),(8826,'and thus would one of the proud youths speak:'),(8827,' “Aye, verily Telemachus is planning our murder.'),(8828,' He will bring men to aid him from sandy Pylos or even from Sparta, so terribly is he set upon it.'),(8829,' Or he means to go to Ephyre, that rich land, to bring from thence deadly drugs,  that he may cast them in the wine-bowl, and destroy us all.”'),(8830,'And again another of the proud youths would say:'),(8831,' “Who knows but he himself as he goes on the hollow ship may perish wandering far from his friends, even as Odysseus did?'),(8832,' So would he cause us yet more labour;'),(8833,' for we should have to divide all his possessions, and his house we should give to his mother to possess, and to him who should wed her.\"'),(8834,'So they spoke, but Telemachus went down to the high-roofed treasure-chamber of his father, a wide room where gold and bronze lay piled, and raiment in chests, and stores of fragrant oil.'),(8835,'  There, too, stood great jars of wine, old and sweet, holding within them an unmixed divine drink, and ranged in order along the wall, if ever Odysseus should return home even after many grievous toils.'),(8836,' Shut were  the double doors, close-fitted; '),(8837,' and there both night and day a stewardess abode, who guarded all in wisdom of mind, Eurycleia, daughter of Ops, son of Peisenor.'),(8838,' To her now Telemachus, when he had called her to the treasure-chamber, spoke, and said:'),(8839,'“Nurse, draw me off wine in jars,  sweet wine that is the choicest next to that which thou guardest ever thinking upon that ill-fated one, if haply Zeus-born Odysseus may come I know not whence, having escaped from death and the fates.'),(8840,' Fill twelve jars and fit them all with covers,'),(8841,'and pour me barley meal into well-sewn skins,'),(8842,' and let there be twenty measures of ground barley meal.'),(8843,'and have all these things brought together; '),(8844,'and have all these things brought together; '),(8845,'for at evening I will fetch them, when my mother goes to her upper chamber and bethinks her of her rest.'),(8846,' For I am going to Sparta and to sandy Pylos  to seek tidings of the return of my dear father, if haply I may hear any.”'),(8847,' \nSo he spoke, and the dear nurse, Eurycleia, uttered a shrill cry, and weeping spoke to him winged words:'),(8848,'“Ah, dear child, how has this thought come into thy mind?'),(8849,' Whither art thou minded to go over the wide earth,  thou who art an only son and well-beloved? '),(8850,' But he hath perished far from his country, the Zeus-born Odysseus, in a strange land; '),(8851,'and these men, so soon as thou art gone, will devise evil for thee hereafter, that thou mayest perish by guile, and themselves divide all these possessions.'),(8852,'Nay, abide here in charge of what is thine;'),(8853,'thou hast no need  to suffer ills and go a wanderer over the unresting sea.”'),(8854,'Then wise Telemachus answered her:'),(8855,' “Take heart, nurse, for not without a god\'s warrant is this my plan. '),(8856,'But swear to tell naught of this to my dear mother until the eleventh or twelfth day shall come,  or until she shall herself miss me and hear that I am gone, that she may not mar her fair flesh with weeping.\"'),(8857,'So he spoke, and the old woman swore a great oath by the gods to say naught.'),(8858,' But when she had sworn and made an end of the oath, straightway she drew for him wine in jars,  and poured barley meal into well-sewn skins; '),(8859,'and Telemachus went to the hall and joined the company of the wooers.'),(8860,'\nThen the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, took other counsel.'),(8861,' In the likeness of Telemachus she went everywhere throughout the city, and to each of the men she drew near and spoke her word,  bidding them gather at even beside the swift ship. '),(8862,'Furthermore, of Noemon, the glorious son of Phronius, she asked a swift ship, '),(8863,'and he promised it to her with a ready heart. '),(8864,' \nNow the sun set and all the ways grew dark. Then she drew the swift ship to the sea and  put in it all the gear that well-benched ships carry.'),(8865,' \nAnd she moored it at the mouth of the harbor, and round about it the goodly company was gathered together,'),(8866,' and the goddess heartened each man.'),(8867,'\nThen again the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, took other counsel.'),(8868,' She went her way to the house of divine Odysseus, '),(8869,' and there began to shed sweet sleep upon the wooers and made them to wander in their drinking, and from their hands she cast the cups.'),(8870,' But they rose to go to their rest throughout the city, and remained no long time seated, for sleep was falling upon their eyelids. '),(8871,'But to Telemachus spoke flashing-eyed Athena,  calling him forth before the stately hall, having likened herself to Mentor both in form and in voice:'),(8872,'\n“Telemachus, already thy well-greaved comrades sit at the oar and await thy setting out.'),(8873,' Come, let us go, that we may not long delay their journey.”'),(8874,'  So saying, Pallas Athena led the way quickly,'),(8875,' and he followed in the footsteps of the goddess.'),(8876,' Now when they had come down to the ship and to the sea, they found on the shore their long-haired comrades, '),(8877,'and the strong and mighty Telemachus spoke among them:'),(8878,'  “Come, friends, let us fetch the stores,'),(8879,'for all are now gathered together in the hall.'),(8880,' My mother knows naught hereof, nor the handmaids either: one only heard my word.\"'),(8881,'Thus saying, he led the way, and they went along with him.'),(8882,' So they brought and  stowed everything in the well-benched ship, as the dear son of Odysseus bade. '),(8883,'Then on board the ship stepped Telemachus, and Athena went before him and sat down in the stern of the ship, '),(8884,' and near her sat Telemachus, '),(8885,' while the men loosed the stern cables and themselves stepped on board, and sat down upon the benches.'),(8886,'  And flashing-eyed Athena sent them a favorable wind, a strong-blowing West wind that sang over the wine-dark sea.'),(8887,' And Telemachus called to his men, and bade them lay hold of the tackling,'),(8888,' and they hearkened to his call.'),(8889,' The mast of fir  they raised and set in the hollow socket, and made it fast with fore-stays, and hauled up the white sail with twisted thongs of ox-hide.'),(8890,' So the wind filled the belly of the sail, and the dark wave sang loudly about the stem of the ship as she went, '),(8891,' and she sped over the wave accomplishing her way.'),(8892,'  Then, when they had made the tackling fast in the swift black ship, they set forth bowls brim full of wine, and poured libations to the immortal gods that are forever, and chiefest of all to the flashing-eyed daughter of Zeus.'),(8893,' So all night long and through the dawn the ship cleft her way.'),(8894,' And now the sun, leaving the beauteous mere, sprang up into the brazen heaven to give light to the immortals and to mortal men on the earth, the giver of grain; '),(8895,'and they came to Pylos, the well-built citadel of Neleus.'),(8896,'  Here the townsfolk on the shore of the sea were offering sacrifice of black bulls to the dark-haired Earth-shaker.'),(8897,' Nine companies there were, and five hundred men sat in each, and in each they held nine bulls ready for sacrifice. '),(8898,'Now when they had tasted the inner parts and were burning the thigh-pieces to the god,  the others put straight in to the shore, and hauled up and furled the sail of the shapely ship, and moored her, and themselves stepped forth.'),(8899,'Forth too from the ship stepped Telemachus, and Athena led the way.'),(8900,' And the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, spake first to him, and said:'),(8901,'“Telemachus, no longer hast thou need to feel shame, no, not a whit. '),(8902,' For to this end hast thou sailed over the sea, that thou mightest seek tidings of thy father,—where the earth covered him, and what fate he met.'),(8903,' But come now, go straightway to Nestor, tamer of horses;'),(8904,'let us learn what counsel he keepeth hid in his breast.'),(8905,' And do thou beseech him thyself that he may tell thee the very truth.'),(8906,'for he is wise indeed.\"'),(8907,'for he is wise indeed.\"'),(8908,'Then wise Telemachus answered her:'),(8909,'and how shall I greet him?'),(8910,'and how shall I greet him?'),(8911,'I am as yet all unversed in subtle speech,'),(8912,' and moreover a young man has shame to question an elder.\"'),(8913,' Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(8914,'“Telemachus, somewhat thou wilt of thyself devise in thy breast, and somewhat heaven too will prompt thee.'),(8915,' For, methinks, not without the favour of the gods hast thou been born and reared.\"'),(8916,'So spake Pallas Athena, and led the way  quickly;'),(8917,' but he followed in the footsteps of the goddess; '),(8918,' There Nestor sat with his sons, and round about his people, making ready the feast, were roasting some of the meat and putting other pieces on spits. '),(8919,' But when they saw the strangers they all came thronging about them,  and clasped their hands in welcome, and bade them sit down. '),(8920,'First Nestor\'s son Peisistratus came near and took both by the hand, and made them to sit down at the feast on soft fleeces upon the sand of the sea, beside his brother Thrasymedes and his father.'),(8921,'  Thereupon he gave them portions of the inner meat and poured wine in a golden cup, '),(8922,'and, pledging her, he spoke to Pallas Athena, daughter of Zeus who bears the aegis:'),(8923,'“Pray now, stranger, to the lord Poseidon,'),(8924,' for his is the feast whereon you have chanced in coming hither.'),(8925,'  And when thou hast poured libations and hast prayed, as is fitting, then give thy friend also the cup of honey-sweet wine that he may pour, since he too, I ween, prays to the immortals;'),(8926,'for all men have need of the gods.'),(8927,' Howbeit he is the younger, of like age with myself, '),(8928,' wherefore to thee first will I give the golden cup.”'),(8929,' \nSo he spake, and placed in her hand the cup of sweet wine.'),(8930,' But Pallas Athena rejoiced at the man\'s wisdom and judgment, in that to her first he gave the golden cup; '),(8931,'and straightway she prayed earnestly to the lord Poseidon:'),(8932,'\n  “Hear me, Poseidon, thou Earth-enfolder, and grudge not in answer to our prayer to bring these deeds to fulfillment.'),(8933,' To Nestor, first of all, and to his sons vouchsafe renown, and then do thou grant to the rest gracious requital for this glorious hecatomb, even to all the men of Pylos; '),(8934,'  and grant furthermore that Telemachus and I may return when we have accomplished all that for which we came hither with our swift black ship.\"'),(8935,'Thus she prayed, and was herself fulfilling all.'),(8936,' Then she gave Telemachus the fair two-handled cup, '),(8937,'and in like manner the dear son of Odysseus prayed.'),(8938,'  Then when they had roasted the outer flesh and drawn it off the spits, they divided the portions and feasted a glorious feast.'),(8939,' But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, spoke first among them:'),(8940,'\n“Now verily is it seemlier to ask and enquire  of the strangers who they are, since now they have had their joy of food.'),(8941,'Whence do ye sail over the watery ways? '),(8942,'Whence do ye sail over the watery ways? '),(8943,' Is it on some business, or do ye wander at random over the sea, even as pirates, who wander hazarding their lives and bringing evil to men of other lands?”'),(8944,'  Then wise Telemachus took courage, and made answer,'),(8945,'for Athena herself put courage in his heart, that he might ask about his father that was gone, and that good report might be his among men:'),(8946,'\n“Nestor, son of Neleus, great glory of the Achaeans,  thou askest whence we are, '),(8947,' and I will surely tell thee.'),(8948,' We have come from Ithaca that is below Neion; '),(8949,' but this business whereof I speak is mine own, and concerns not the people.'),(8950,' I come after the wide-spread rumor of my father, if haply I may hear of it, even of goodly Odysseus of the steadfast heart, who once, men say,  fought by thy side and sacked the city of the Trojans. '),(8951,' For of all men else, as many as warred with the Trojans, we learn where each man died a woeful death, but of him the son of Cronos has made even the death to be past learning; '),(8952,'for no man can tell surely where he hath died,—  whether he was overcome by foes on the mainland, or on the deep among the waves of Amphitrite.'),(8953,' Therefore am I now come to thy knees, if perchance thou wilt be willing to tell me of his woeful death, whether thou sawest it haply with thine own eyes, or didst hear from some other the story  of his wanderings; '),(8954,'for beyond all men did his mother bear him to sorrow. '),(8955,' And do thou nowise out of ruth or pity for me speak soothing words, but tell me truly how thou didst come to behold him. '),(8956,'I beseech thee, if ever my father, noble Odysseus, promised aught to thee of word or deed and fulfilled it  in the land of the Trojans, where you Achaeans suffered woes, be mindful of it now, I pray thee, and tell me the very truth.” '),(8957,' \nThen the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, answered him:'),(8958,'“My friend, since thou hast recalled to my mind the sorrow which we endured in that land, we sons of the Achaeans, unrestrained in daring,—  all that we endured on shipboard, as we roamed after booty over the misty deep whithersoever Achilles led; and all our fightings around the great city of king Priam;'),(8959,'—lo, there all our best were slain.'),(8960,' There lies warlike Aias, there Achilles,  there Patroclus, the peer of the gods in counsel; and there my own dear son, strong alike and peerless, Antilochus, pre-eminent in speed of foot and as a warrior.'),(8961,' Aye, and many other ills we suffered besides these; '),(8962,' who of mortal men could tell them all?'),(8963,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 3.115-3.116'),(8964,'  Nay, if for five years\' space or six years\' space thou wert to abide here, and ask of all the woes which the goodly Achaeans endured there, ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 115 to line 117'),(8965,' For nine years\' space were we busied plotting their ruin with all manner of wiles; and hardly did the son of Cronos bring it to pass.'),(8966,'  There no man ventured to vie with him in counsel, since goodly Odysseus far excelled in all manner of wiles,—thy father, if indeed thou art his son.'),(8967,' Amazement holds me as I look on thee, '),(8968,'for verily thy speech is like his; nor would one think  that a younger man would speak so like him. '),(8969,'Now all the time that we were there goodly Odysseus and I never spoke at variance either in the assembly or in the council, but being of one mind advised the Argives with wisdom and shrewd counsel how all might be for the best.'),(8970,'  But when we had sacked the lofty city of Priam, and had gone away in our ships, and a god had scattered the Achaeans, then, even then, Zeus planned in his heart a woeful return for the Argives, for in no wise prudent or just were all.'),(8971,' Wherefore many of them met an evil fate  through the fell wrath of the flashing-eyed goddess, the daughter of the mighty sire, '),(8972,'for she caused strife between the two sons of Atreus.'),(8973,' Now these two called to an assembly all the Achaeans, recklessly and in no due order, at set of sun—and they came heavy with wine, the sons of the Achaeans,—  and they spoke their word, and told wherefore they had gathered the host together.'),(8974,' \nThen in truth Menelaus bade all the Achaeans think of their return over the broad back of the sea, but in no wise did he please Agamemnon, '),(8975,' for he was fain to hold back the host and to offer holy hecatombs,  that he might appease the dread wrath of Athena,—fool! nor knew he this, that with her was to be no hearkening;'),(8976,' for the mind of the gods that are forever is not quickly turned.'),(8977,' So these two stood bandying harsh words; '),(8978,' but the well-greaved Achaeans sprang up  with a wondrous din, and two-fold plans found favour with them.'),(8979,' That night we rested, each side pondering hard thoughts against the other,'),(8980,' for Zeus was bringing upon us an evil doom, '),(8981,'but in the morning some of us launched our ships upon the bright sea, and put on board our goods and the low-girdled women.'),(8982,'  Half, indeed, of the host held back and remained there with Agamemnon, son of Atreus, shepherd of the host, '),(8983,'but half of us embarked and rowed away; '),(8984,'and swiftly the ships sailed, for a god made smooth the cavernous sea.'),(8985,' But when we came to Tenedos, we offered sacrifice to the gods,  being eager to reach our homes, '),(8986,'howbeit Zeus did not yet purpose our return, stubborn god, who roused evil strife again a second time.'),(8987,' Then some turned back their curved ships and departed, even the lord Odysseus, the wise and crafty-minded, with his company, once more showing favour to Agamemnon, son of Atreus; '),(8988,' but I with the full company of ships that followed me fled on, for I knew that the god was devising evil.'),(8989,' And the warlike son of Tydeus fled and urged on his men; '),(8990,'and late upon our track came fair-haired Menelaus, and overtook us in Lesbos, as we were debating the long voyage,  whether we should sail to sea-ward of rugged Chios, toward the isle Psyria, keeping Chios itself on our left, or to land-ward of Chios past windy Mimas.'),(8991,' So we asked the god to shew us a sign, '),(8992,' and he shewed it us, and bade us cleave through the midst of the sea to Euboea,  that we might the soonest escape from misery.'),(8993,'And a shrill wind sprang up to blow,'),(8994,' and the ships ran swiftly over the teeming ways, and at night put in to Geraestus.'),(8995,' There on the altar of Poseidon we laid many thighs of bulls, thankful to have traversed the great sea.'),(8996,'  It was the fourth day when in Argos the company of Diomedes, son of Tydeus, tamer of horses, stayed their shapely ships; '),(8997,'but I held on toward Pylos, and the wind was not once quenched from the time when the god first sent it forth to blow. '),(8998,' \n“Thus I came, dear child, without tidings, nor know I aught  of those others, who of the Achaeans were saved, and who were lost. '),(8999,'But what tidings I have heard as I abide in our halls thou shalt hear, as is right, nor will I hide it from thee.'),(9000,' Safely, they say, came the Myrmidons that rage with the spear, whom the famous son of great-hearted Achilles led;  and safely Philoctetes, the glorious son of Poias. '),(9001,'All his company, too, did Idomeneus bring to Crete, all who escaped the war, and the sea robbed him of none.'),(9002,' But of the son of Atreus you have yourselves heard, far off though you are, how he came, and how Aegisthus devised for him a woeful doom.'),(9003,'  Yet verily he paid the reckoning therefor in terrible wise,'),(9004,' so good a thing is it that a son be left behind a man at his death, since that son took vengeance on his father\'s slayer, the guileful Aegisthus, for that he slew his glorious father.'),(9005,' Thou, too, friend, for I see thou art a comely man and tall,  be thou valiant, that many an one among men yet to be born may praise thee.\"'),(9006,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(9007,' “Nestor, son of Neleus, great glory of the Achaeans, yea verily that son took vengeance, and the Achaeans shall spread his fame abroad, that men who are yet to be may hear thereof.'),(9008,'  O that the gods would clothe me with such strength, that I might take vengeance on the wooers for their grievous sin, who in wantonness devise mischief against me. '),(9009,'But lo, the gods have spun for me no such happiness, for me or for my father; '),(9010,'and now I must in any case endure.”'),(9011,'  Then the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, answered him: '),(9012,'“Friend, since thou calledst this to my mind and didst speak of it, they say that many wooers for the hand of thy mother devise evils in thy halls in thy despite.'),(9013,' Tell me, art thou willingly thus oppressed, or do the people  throughout the land hate thee, following the voice of a god? '),(9014,'Who knows but Odysseus may some day come and take vengeance on them for their violent deeds,—he alone, it may be, or even all the host of the Achaeans? '),(9015,'Ah, would that flashing-eyed Athena might choose to love thee even as then she cared exceedingly for glorious Odysseus  in the land of the Trojans, where we Achaeans suffered woes. For never yet have I seen the gods so manifestly shewing love, as Pallas Athena did to him, standing manifest by his side. If she would be pleased to love thee in such wise and would care for thee at heart, then would many a one of them utterly forget marriage.\"'),(9016,' Then wise Telemachus answered him: '),(9017,' “Old man, in no wise do I deem that this word will be brought to pass.'),(9018,'amazement holds me.'),(9019,'amazement holds me.'),(9020,' No hope have I that this will come to pass, no, not though the gods should so will it.” '),(9021,' \nThen the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, spoke to him, and said: '),(9022,' \n “Telemachus, what a word has escaped the barrier of thy teeth! '),(9023,' \nEasily might a god who willed it bring a man safe home, even from afar.'),(9024,' But for myself, I had rather endure many grievous toils ere I reached home and saw the day of my returning, than after my return be slain at my hearth, as Agamemnon  was slain by the guile of Aegisthus and of his own wife. '),(9025,'But of a truth death that is common to all the gods themselves cannot ward from a man they love, when the fell fate of grievous death shall strike him down.\"'),(9026,'Then wise Telemachus answered her: '),(9027,' “Mentor, no longer let us tell of these things despite our grief. '),(9028,' For him no return can ever more be brought to pass; nay, ere this the immortals have devised for him death and black fate.'),(9029,' But now I would make enquiry and ask Nestor regarding another matter, since beyond all others he knows judgments and wisdom; '),(9030,' for thrice, men say, has he been king for a generation of men, '),(9031,'and like unto an immortal he seems to me to look upon.'),(9032,' Nestor, son of Neleus, do thou tell me truly:'),(9033,' how was the son of Atreus, wide-ruling Agamemnon, slain?'),(9034,' Where was Menelaus?'),(9035,' What death did  guileful Aegisthus plan for the king, since he slew a man mightier far than himself? '),(9036,'Was Menelaus not in Achaean Argos, but wandering elsewhere among men, so that Aegisthus took heart and did the murderous deed?\"'),(9037,'Then the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, answered him:'),(9038,' “Then verily, my child, will I tell thee all the truth.'),(9039,'  Lo, of thine own self thou dost guess how this matter would have fallen out, if the son of Atreus, fair-haired Menelaus, on his return from Troy had found Aegisthus in his halls alive. '),(9040,' Then for him not even in death would they have piled the up-piled earth, but the dogs and birds would have torn him  as he lay on the plain far from the city, nor would any of the Achaean women have bewailed him; '),(9041,'for monstrous was the deed he devised.'),(9042,' We on our part abode there in Troy fulfilling our many toils; '),(9043,'but he, at ease in a nook of horse-pasturing Argos, ever sought to beguile with words the wife of Agamemnon.'),(9044,'  Now at the first she put from her the unseemly deed, the beautiful Clytemnestra, '),(9045,'for she had an understanding heart; '),(9046,'and with her was furthermore a minstrel whom the son of Atreus straitly charged, when he set forth for the land of Troy, to guard his wife. '),(9047,'But when at length the doom of the gods bound her that she should be overcome,  then verily Aegisthus took the minstrel to a desert isle and left him to be the prey and spoil of birds; and her, willing as he was willing, he led to his own house.'),(9048,' And many thigh-pieces he burned upon the holy altars of the gods, and many offerings he hung up, woven stuffs and gold,  since he had accomplished a mighty deed beyond all his heart had hoped.'),(9049,' \n“Now we were sailing together on our way from Troy, the son of Atreus and I, in all friendship; '),(9050,'but when we came to holy Sunium, the cape of Athens, there Phoebus Apollo  assailed with his gentle shafts and slew the helmsman of Menelaus, as he held in his hands the steering-oar of the speeding ship, even Phrontis, son of Onetor, who excelled the tribes of men in piloting a ship when the storm winds blow strong.'),(9051,' So Menelaus tarried there, though eager for his journey,  that he might bury his comrade and over him pay funeral rites.'),(9052,'But when he in his turn, as he passed over the wine-dark sea in the hollow ships, reached in swift course the steep height of Malea, then verily Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, planned for him a hateful path and poured upon him the blasts of shrill winds,  and the waves were swollen to huge size, like unto mountains. '),(9053,'Then, parting his ships in twain, he brought some to Crete, where the Cydonians dwelt about the streams of Iardanus.'),(9054,' Now there is a smooth cliff, sheer towards the sea, on the border of Gortyn in the misty deep, '),(9055,' where the Southwest Wind drives the great wave against the headland on the left toward Phaestus, and a little rock holds back a great wave.'),(9056,' Thither came some of his ships, and the men with much ado escaped destruction, howbeit the ships the waves dashed to pieces against the reef.'),(9057,' But the five other dark-prowed ships  the wind, as it bore them, and the wave brought to Egypt.'),(9058,' So he was wandering there with his ships among men of strange speech, gathering much livelihood and gold;'),(9059,' but meanwhile Aegisthus devised this woeful work at home.'),(9060,'  Seven years he reigned over Mycenae, rich in gold, after slaying the son of Atreus, and the people were subdued under him;'),(9061,' but in the eighth came as his bane the goodly Orestes back from Athens, and slew his father\'s murderer,  the guileful Aegisthus, for that he had slain his glorious father. '),(9062,' Now when he had slain him, he made a funeral feast for the Argives over his hateful mother and the craven Aegisthus; '),(9063,'and on the self-same day there came to him Menelaus, good at the war-cry, bringing much treasure, even all the burden that his ships could bear.'),(9064,'“So do not thou, my friend, wander long far from home, leaving thy wealth behind thee and men in thy house  so insolent, lest they divide and devour all thy wealth, and thou shalt have gone on a fruitless journey.'),(9065,' But to Menelaus I bid and command thee to go, '),(9066,'for he has but lately come from a strange land, from a folk whence no one would hope in his heart  to return, whom the storms had once driven astray into a sea so great, whence the very birds do not fare in the space of a year, so great is it and terrible.'),(9067,' But now go thy way with thy ship and thy comrades, '),(9068,' or, if thou wilt go by land, here are chariot and horses at hand for thee,  and here at thy service are my sons, who will be thy guides to goodly Lacedaemon, where lives fair-haired Menelaus.'),(9069,' And do thou beseech him thyself that he may tell thee the very truth.'),(9070,' for he is wise indeed.” '),(9071,' for he is wise indeed.” '),(9072,' \nSo he spoke, and the sun set, and darkness came on. '),(9073,' \n Then among them spoke the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena: '),(9074,' \n“Old man, of a truth thou hast told this tale aright.'),(9075,' But come, cut out the tongues of the victims and mix the wine, that when we have poured libations to Poseidon and the other immortals, we may bethink us of sleep; '),(9076,'for it is the time thereto.'),(9077,'  Even now has the light gone down beneath the darkness,'),(9078,' and it is not fitting to sit long at the feast of the gods, but to go our way.\"'),(9079,'So spoke the daughter of Zeus, and they hearkenened to her voice.'),(9080,' Heralds poured water over their hands, and youths filled the bowls brim full of drink,  and served out to all, pouring first drops for libation into the cups.'),(9081,' Then they cast the tongues upon the fire, and, rising up, poured libations upon them.'),(9082,' But when they had poured libations and had drunk to their heart\'s content, then verily Athena and godlike Telemachus were both fain to return to the hollow ship; '),(9083,' but Nestor on his part sought to stay them, and he spoke to them, saying:'),(9084,'“This may Zeus forbid, and the other immortal gods, that ye should go from my house to your swift ship as from one utterly without raiment and poor, who has not cloaks and blankets in plenty in his house,  whereon both he and his guests may sleep softly.'),(9085,' Nay, in my house there are cloaks and fair blankets.'),(9086,' Never surely shall the dear son of this man Odysseus lie down upon the deck of a ship, while I yet live and children after me are left in my halls  to entertain strangers, even whosoever shall come to my house.\"'),(9087,'Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(9088,' “Well indeed hast thou spoken in this, old friend,'),(9089,' and it were fitting for Telemachus to hearken to thee, since it is far better thus.'),(9090,' But while he shall now follow with thee, that he may sleep  in thy halls, '),(9091,' I for my part will go to the black ship, that I may hearten my comrades and tell them all.'),(9092,' For alone among them I declare that I am an older man;'),(9093,' the others are younger who follow in friendship, all of them of like age with great-hearted Telemachus.'),(9094,'  There will I lay me down by the hollow black ship this night, '),(9095,'but in the morning I will go to the great-hearted Cauconians, where a debt is owing to me, in no wise new or small.'),(9096,' But do thou send this man on his way with a chariot and with thy son, since he has come to thy house,'),(9097,' and give him horses,  the fleetest thou host in running and the best in strength.”'),(9098,' \nSo spoke the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, and she departed in the likeness of a sea-eagle; '),(9099,' \nand amazement fell upon all at the sight, '),(9100,'and the old man marvelled, when his eyes beheld it.'),(9101,' And he grasped the hand of Telemachus, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(9102,'\n  “Friend, in no wise do I think that thou wilt prove a base man or a craven, if verily when thou art so young the gods follow thee to be thy guides.'),(9103,' For truly this is none other of those that have their dwellings on Olympus but the daughter of Zeus, Tritogeneia, the maid most glorious, she that honored also thy noble father among the Argives.'),(9104,'  Nay, O Queen, be gracious, and grant to me fair renown, to me and to my sons and to my revered wife; '),(9105,'and to thee in return will I sacrifice a sleek heifer, broad of brow, unbroken, which no man hath yet led beneath the yoke.'),(9106,' Her will I sacrifice, and I will overlay her horns with gold.\"'),(9107,' So he spoke in prayer, and Pallas Athena heard him. '),(9108,'Then the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, led them, his sons and the husbands of his daughters, to his beautiful palace.'),(9109,' And when they reached the glorious palace of the king, they sat down in rows on the chairs and high seats; '),(9110,' and on their coming the old man mixed for them a bowl of sweet wine, which now in the eleventh year the housewife opened, when she had loosed the string that held the lid.'),(9111,' Thereof the old man bade mix a bowl, and earnestly he prayed, as he poured libations, to Athena, the daughter of Zeus who bears the aegis.'),(9112,'\n  But when they had poured libations, and had drunk to their heart\'s content, they went, each to his home, to take their rest. But the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, bade Telemachus, the dear son of divine Odysseus, to sleep there on a corded bedstead under the echoing portico,  and by him Peisistratus, of the good ashen spear, a leader of men, who among his sons was still unwed in the palace.'),(9113,' But he himself slept in the inmost chamber of the lofty house, and beside him lay the lady his wife, who had strewn the couch. '),(9114,' \nSoon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered,  up from his bed rose the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, and went forth and sat down on the polished stones which were before his lofty doors, white and glistening as with oil.'),(9115,' On these of old was wont to sit Neleus, the peer of the gods in counsel; '),(9116,' but he ere this had been stricken by fate and had gone to the house of Hades, and now there sat upon them in his turn Nestor of Gerenia, the warder of the Achaeans, holding a sceptre in his hands.'),(9117,' About him his sons gathered in a throng as they came forth from their chambers, Echephron and Stratius and Perseus and Aretus and godlike Thrasymedes; '),(9118,' and to these thereafter came as the sixth the lord Peisistratus. And they led godlike Telemachus and made him sit beside them;'),(9119,' and the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, was first to speak among them:'),(9120,'\n“Quickly, my dear children, fulfil my desire, that first of all the gods I may propitiate Athena,  who came to me in manifest presence to the rich feast of the god. '),(9121,'Come now, let one go to the plain for a heifer, that she may come speedily, and that the neat herd may drive her; '),(9122,'and let one go to the black ship of great-hearted Telemachus and bring all his comrades, and let him leave two men only; '),(9123,' and let one again bid the goldsmith Laerces come hither, that he may overlay the heifer\'s horns with gold. '),(9124,'And do ye others abide here together; and bid the handmaids within to make ready a feast throughout our glorious halls, to fetch seats, and logs to set on either side of the altar, and to bring clear water.\"'),(9125,'  So he spoke, and they all set busily to work. '),(9126,'The heifer came from the plain and from the swift, shapely ship came the comrades of great-hearted Telemachus; the smith came, bearing in his hands his tools of bronze, the implements of his craft, anvil and hammer and well-made tongs,  wherewith he wrought the gold; '),(9127,' and Athena came to accept the sacrifice.'),(9128,' Then the old man, Nestor, the driver of chariots, gave gold,  '),(9129,' and the smith prepared it, and overlaid therewith the horns of the heifer, that the goddess might rejoice when she beheld the offering.'),(9130,' And Stratius and goodly Echephron led the heifer by the horns, '),(9131,'  and Aretus came from the chamber, bringing them water for the hands in a basin embossed with flowers, and in the other hand he held barley grains in a basket; and Thrasymedes, steadfast in fight, stood by, holding in his hands a sharp axe, to fell the heifer; '),(9132,' and Perseus held the bowl for the blood. '),(9133,'Then the old man, Nestor, driver of chariots,  began the opening rite of hand-washing and sprinkling with barley grains, and earnestly he prayed to Athena, cutting off as first offering the hair from the head, and casting it into the fire. '),(9134,' \nNow when they had prayed, and had strewn the barley grains, straightway the son of Nestor, Thrasymedes, high of heart, came near and dealt the blow; '),(9135,'and the axe cut through the sinews  of the neck, and loosened the strength of the heifer. '),(9136,'Then the women raised the sacred cry, the daughters and the sons\' wives and the revered wife of Nestor, Eurydice, the eldest of the daughters of Clymenus, '),(9137,' and the men raised the heifer\'s head from the broad-wayed earth and held it,'),(9138,' and Peisistratus, leader of men, cut the throat.'),(9139,'  And when the black blood had flowed from her and the life had left the bones, at once they cut up the body and straightway cut out the thigh-pieces all in due order, and covered them with a double layer of fat, and laid raw flesh upon them.'),(9140,' Then the old man burned them on billets of wood, and poured over them sparkling wine,'),(9141,'  and beside him the young men held in their hands the five-pronged forks. '),(9142,'But when the thigh-pieces were wholly burned, and they had tasted the inner parts, they cut up the rest and spitted and roasted it, holding the pointed spits in their hands.'),(9143,'\nMeanwhile the fair Polycaste,  the youngest daughter of Nestor, son of Neleus, bathed Telemachus.'),(9144,' And when she had bathed him and anointed him richly with oil, and had cast about him a fair cloak and a tunic, forth from the bath he came in form like unto the immortals;'),(9145,' and he went and sat down by Nestor, the shepherd of the people.'),(9146,' Now when they had roasted the outer flesh and had drawn it off the spits, they sat down and feasted, '),(9147,' and worthy men waited on them, pouring wine into golden cups.'),(9148,' But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, was first to speak, saying:'),(9149,'\n  “My sons, up, yoke for Telemachus horses with beautiful mane beneath the car, that he may get forward on his journey.\"'),(9150,'So he spoke, and they readily hearkened and obeyed; and quickly they yoked beneath the car the swift horses.'),(9151,' And the housewife placed in the car bread and wine  and dainties, such as kings, fostered of Zeus, are wont to eat.'),(9152,' Then Telemachus mounted the beautiful car,'),(9153,' and Peisistratus, son of Nestor, a leader of men, mounted beside him, and took the reins in his hands. He touched the horses with the whip to start them, and nothing loath the pair sped on  to the plain, and left the steep citadel of Pylos.'),(9154,'So all day long they shook the yoke which they bore about their necks.'),(9155,' Now the sun set and all the ways grew dark. And they came to Pherae, to the house of Diocles, son of Ortilochus, whom Alpheus begot.'),(9156,'   There they spent the night, and before them he set the entertainment due to strangers.'),(9157,'So soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, they yoked the horses and mounted the inlaid car, '),(9158,'and drove forth from the gateway and the echoing portico.'),(9159,' Then Peisistratus touched the horses with the whip to start them, and nothing loath the pair sped onward.'),(9160,'  So they came to the wheat-bearing plain, and thereafter pressed on toward their journey\'s end,'),(9161,'so well did their swift horses bear them on.'),(9162,' And the sun set and all the ways grew dark.'),(9163,' And they came to the hollow land of Lacedaemon with its many ravines, and drove to the palace of glorious Menelaus.'),(9164,' Him they found giving a marriage feast to his many kinsfolk for his noble son and daughter within his house.'),(9165,' His daughter he was sending to the son of Achilles, breaker of the ranks of men,'),(9166,'for in the land of Troy he first had promised and pledged that he would give her, and now the gods were bringing their marriage to pass.'),(9167,' Her then he was sending forth with horses and chariots to go her way to the glorious city of the Myrmidons, over whom her lord was king; '),(9168,' but for his son he was bringing to his home from Sparta the daughter of Alector, even for the stalwart Megapenthes, who was his son well-beloved, born of a slave woman;'),(9169,' for to Helen the gods vouchsafed issue no more after that she had at the first borne her lovely child, Hermione, who had the beauty of golden Aphrodite. '),(9170,' So they were feasting in the great high-roofed hall, the neighbors and kinsfolk of glorious Menelaus, and making merry;'),(9171,'and among them a divine minstrel was singing to the lyre, and two tumblers whirled up and down through the midst of them, as he began his song.'),(9172,' Then the two, the prince Telemachus and the glorious son of Nestor, halted at the gateway of the palace, they and their two horses.'),(9173,'And the lord Eteoneus came forth and saw them, the busy squire of glorious Menelaus; and he went through the hall to bear the tidings to the shepherd of the people.  So he came near and spoke to him winged words:'),(9174,'“Here are two strangers, Menelaus, fostered of Zeus, two men that are like the seed of great Zeus.'),(9175,' But tell me, shall we unyoke for them their swift horses, or send them on their way to some other host, who will give them entertainment?”'),(9176,' Then, stirred to sore displeasure, fair-haired Menelaus spoke to him:'),(9177,'“Aforetime thou was not wont to be a fool, Eteoneus, son of Boethous,'),(9178,'but now like a child thou talkest folly.'),(9179,' Surely we two ate full often hospitable cheer of other men, ere we came hither in the hope that Zeus  would hereafter grant us respite from sorrow.'),(9180,'Nay, unyoke the strangers\' horses, and lead the men forward into the house, that they may feast.”'),(9181,'So he spoke, and the other hastened through the hall, and called to the other busy squires to follow along with him. '),(9182,'They loosed the sweating horses from beneath the yoke  and tied them at the stalls of the horses, and flung before them spelt, and mixed therewith white barley. Then they tilted the chariot against the bright entrance walls, and led the men into the divine palace.'),(9183,' But at the sight they marvelled as they passed through the palace of the king, fostered of Zeus;'),(9184,' for there was a gleam as of sun or moon over the high-roofed house of glorious Menelaus.'),(9185,'But when they had satisfied their eyes with gazing they went into the polished baths and bathed. '),(9186,' And when the maids had bathed them and anointed them with oil,  and had cast about them fleecy cloaks and tunics, they sat down on chairs beside Menelaus, son of Atreus.'),(9187,' Then a handmaid brought water for the hands in a fair pitcher of gold, and poured it over a silver basin for them to wash,'),(9188,' and beside them drew up a polished table.'),(9189,'  And the grave housewife brought and set before them bread, and therewith dainties in abundance, giving freely of her store.'),(9190,'And a carver lifted up and placed before them platters of all manner of meats, and set by them golden goblets. '),(9191,'Then fair-haired Menelaus greeted the two and said:'),(9192,' “Take of the food, and be glad,'),(9193,'and then when you have supped, we will ask you who among men you are;'),(9194,'for in you two the breed of your sires is not lost, but ye are of the breed of men that are sceptred kings, fostered of Zeus; for base churls could not beget such sons as you.”'),(9195,' So saying he took in his hands roast meat and set it before them, even the fat ox-chine which they had set before himself as a mess of honor.'),(9196,' So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them.'),(9197,' But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, lo, then Telemachus spoke to the son of Nestor,  holding his head close to him, that the others might not hear:'),(9198,'“Son of Nestor, dear to this heart of mine, mark the flashing of bronze throughout the echoing halls, and the flashing of gold, of electrum, of silver, and of ivory.'),(9199,' Of such sort, methinks, is the court of Olympian Zeus within,  such untold wealth is here; '),(9200,'amazement holds me as I look.”'),(9201,'Now as he spoke fair-haired Menelaus heard him, and he spoke and addressed them with winged words:'),(9202,'“Dear children, with Zeus verily no mortal man could vie,'),(9203,' for everlasting are his halls and his possessions;'),(9204,' but of men another might vie with me in wealth or haply might not.'),(9205,' For of a truth after many woes and wide wanderings I brought my wealth home in my ships and came in the eighth year. Over Cyprus and Phoenicia I wandered, and Egypt, and I came to the Ethiopians and the Sidonians and the Erembi,  and to Libya, where the lambs are horned from their birth.'),(9206,' For there the ewes bear their young thrice within the full course of the year; '),(9207,'there neither master nor shepherd has any lack of cheese or of meat or of sweet milk, but the flocks ever yield milk to the milking the year through.'),(9208,'  While I wandered in those lands gathering much livelihood, meanwhile another slew my brother by stealth and at unawares, by the guile of his accursed wife.'),(9209,' Thus, thou mayest see, I have no joy in being lord of this wealth;'),(9210,'and you may well have heard of this from your fathers, whosoever they  may be, for full much did I suffer, and let fall into ruin a stately house and one stored with much goodly treasure.'),(9211,'Would that I dwelt in my halls with but a third part of this wealth, and that those men were safe who then perished in the broad land of Troy far from horse-pasturing Argos. '),(9212,' And yet, though I often sit in my halls weeping and sorrowing for them all—one moment indeed I ease my heart with weeping, and then again I cease,'),(9213,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 4.103'),(9214,'yet for them all I mourn not so much, despite my grief,  as for one only, who makes me to loathe both sleep and food, when I think of him; for no one of the Achaeans toiled so much as Odysseus toiled and endured. '),(9215,'But to himself, as it seems, his portion was to be but woe, and for me there is sorrow never to be forgotten for him, in that he is gone so long, nor do we know aught  whether he be alive or dead.'),(9216,' Mourned is he, I ween, by the old man Laertes, and by constant Penelope, and by Telemachus, whom he left a new-born child in his house.”'),(9217,'So he spoke, and in Telemachus he roused the desire to weep for his father.'),(9218,' Tears from his eyelids he let fall upon the ground, when he heard his father\'s name,  and with both hands held up his purple cloak before his eyes.'),(9219,'And Menelaus noted him, and debated in mind and heart whether he should leave him to speak of his father himself, or whether he should first question him and prove him in each thing.'),(9220,' While he pondered thus in mind and heart, forth then from her fragrant high-roofed chamber came Helen, like Artemis of the golden arrows;'),(9221,'and with her came Adraste, and placed for her a chair, beautifully wrought, and Alcippe brought a rug of soft wool  and Phylo a silver basket, which Alcandre had given her, the wife of Polybus, who dwelt in Thebes of Egypt, where greatest store of wealth is laid up in men\'s houses.'),(9222,' He gave to Menelaus two silver baths and two tripods and ten talents of gold. '),(9223,' And besides these, his wife gave to Helen also beautiful gifts,—'),(9224,'a golden distaff and a basket with wheels beneath did she give, a basket of silver, and with gold were the rims thereof gilded.'),(9225,' This then the handmaid, Phylo, brought and placed beside her, filled with finely-spun yarn,'),(9226,'and across it  was laid the distaff laden with violet-dark wool.'),(9227,'So Helen sat down upon the chair, and below was a footstool for the feet;'),(9228,' and at once she questioned her husband on each matter, and said:'),(9229,'“Do we know, Menelaus, fostered of Zeus, who these men declare themselves to be who have come to our house? '),(9230,' Nay, my heart bids me speak.'),(9231,' Nay, my heart bids me speak.'),(9232,' For never yet, I declare, saw I one so like another, whether man or woman—amazement holds me, as I look—as this man is like the son of great-hearted Odysseus, even Telemachus, whom that warrior left a new-born child in his house, when for the sake of shameless me ye Achaeans came up under the walls of Troy, pondering in your hearts fierce war.” '),(9233,' \nThen fair-haired Menelaus answered her:'),(9234,' “Even so do I myself now note it, wife, as thou markest the likeness.'),(9235,'Such were his feet, such his hands,  and the glances of his eyes, and his head and hair above.'),(9236,'And verily but now, as I made mention of Odysseus and was telling of all the woe and toil he endured for my sake, this youth let fall a bitter tear from beneath his brows, holding up his purple cloak before his eyes.”'),(9237,' Then Peisistratus, son of Nestor, answered him:'),(9238,'“Menelaus, son of Atreus, fostered of Zeus, leader of hosts, his son indeed this youth is, as thou sayest.'),(9239,'But he is of prudent mind and feels shame at heart thus on his first coming to make a show of forward words  in the presence of thee, in whose voice we both take delight as in a god\'s. '),(9240,'But the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, sent me forth to go with him as his guide,'),(9241,'for he was eager to see thee, that thou mightest put in his heart some word or some deed. '),(9242,'For many sorrows has a son  in his halls when his father is gone, when there are none other to be his helpers, even as it is now with Telemachus; his father is gone, and there are no others among the people who might ward off ruin.”'),(9243,'Then fair-haired Menelaus answered him and said: '),(9244,'“Lo now, verily is there come to my house the son of a man well-beloved,  who for my sake endured many toils. '),(9245,'And I thought that if he came back I should give him welcome beyond all the other Argives, if Olympian Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, had granted to us two a return in our swift ships over the sea. '),(9246,'And in Argos I would have given him a city to dwell in, and would have built him a house,  when I had brought him from Ithaca with his goods and his son and all his people, driving out the dwellers of some one city among those that lie round about and obey me myself as their lord.'),(9247,'Then, living here, should we ofttimes have met together,'),(9248,'nor would aught have parted us, loving and joying in one another,  until the black cloud of death enfolded us.'),(9249,'Howbeit of this, methinks, the god himself must have been jealous, who to that hapless man alone vouchsafed no return.” '),(9250,'So he spoke, and in them all aroused the desire of lament.'),(9251,' Argive Helen wept, the daughter of Zeus,  Telemachus wept, and Menelaus, son of Atreus, nor could the son of Nestor keep his eyes tearless.'),(9252,' For he thought in his heart of peerless Antilochus, whom the glorious son of the bright Dawn had slain.'),(9253,'Thinking of him, he spoke winged words:'),(9254,' “Son of Atreus, old Nestor used ever to say that thou wast wise above all men, whenever we made mention of thee in his halls and questioned one another.'),(9255,'And now, if it may in any wise be, hearken to me, '),(9256,'for I take no joy in weeping at supper time,—and moreover  early dawn will soon be here. '),(9257,'I count it indeed no blame to weep for any mortal who has died and met his fate.'),(9258,'Yea, this is the only due we pay to miserable mortals, to cut the hair and let a tear fall from the cheeks.'),(9259,'For a brother of mine, too, is dead, nowise the meanest  of the Argives,'),(9260,'and thou mayest well have known him.'),(9261,'As for me, I never met him nor saw him;'),(9262,'but men say that Antilochus was above all others pre-eminent in speed of foot and as a warrior.”'),(9263,'Then fair-haired Menelaus answered him and said:'),(9264,' “My friend, truly thou hast said all that a wise man  might say or do, even one that was older than thou;'),(9265,' for from such a father art thou sprung, wherefore thou dost even speak wisely. Easily known is the seed of that man for whom the son of Cronos spins the thread of good fortune at marriage and at birth, even as now he has granted to Nestor throughout all his days continually that  he should himself reach a sleek old age in his halls, and that his sons in their turn should be wise and most valiant with the spear.'),(9266,'But we will cease the weeping which but now was made, and let us once more think of our supper, and let them pour water over our hands.'),(9267,' Tales there will be in the morning also  for Telemachus and me to tell to one another to the full.”'),(9268,'So he spoke, and Asphalion poured water over their hands, the busy squire of glorious Menelaus.'),(9269,'And they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them. '),(9270,' \nThen Helen, daughter of Zeus, took other counsel.'),(9271,' Straightway she cast into the wine of which they were drinking a drug to quiet all pain and strife, and bring forgetfulness of every ill. '),(9272,'Whoso should drink this down, when it is mingled in the bowl, would not in the course of that day let a tear fall down over his cheeks,  no, not though his mother and father should lie there dead, or though before his face men should slay with the sword his brother or dear son, and his own eyes beheld it.'),(9273,'Such cunning drugs had the daughter of Zeus, drugs of healing, which Polydamna, the wife of Thon, had given her, a woman of Egypt, for there the earth, the giver of grain, bears greatest store  of drugs, many that are healing when mixed, and many that are baneful;'),(9274,'there every man is a physician, wise above human kind;'),(9275,'for they are of the race of Paeeon.'),(9276,'Now when she had cast in the drug, and had bidden pour forth the wine, again she made answer, and said:'),(9277,' “Menelaus, son of Atreus, fostered of Zeus, and ye that are here, sons of noble men—'),(9278,'though now to one and now to another Zeus gives good and ill,'),(9279,'for he can do all things,—'),(9280,'now verily sit ye in the halls and feast, and take ye joy in telling tales,'),(9281,'for I will tell what fitteth the time.'),(9282,' All things I cannot tell or recount, even all the labours of Odysseus of the steadfast heart;'),(9283,'but what a thing was this which that mighty man wrought and endured in the land of the Trojans, where you Achaens suffered woes!'),(9284,'Marring his own body with cruel blows,  and flinging a wretched garment about his shoulders, in the fashion of a slave he entered the broad-wayed city of the foe,'),(9285,'and he hid himself under the likeness of another, a beggar, he who was in no wise such an one at the ships of the Achaeans.'),(9286,'In this likeness he entered the city of the Trojans, and all of them were but as babes.'),(9287,'  I alone recognized him in this disguise, and questioned him,'),(9288,'but he in his cunning sought to avoid me. '),(9289,'Howbeit when I was bathing him and anointing him with oil, and had put on him raiment, and sworn a mighty oath not to make him known among the Trojans as Odysseus  before that he reached the swift ships and the huts, then at length he told me all the purpose of the Achaeans.'),(9290,'And when he had slain many of the Trojans with the long sword, he returned to the company of the Argives and brought back plentiful tidings. '),(9291,'Then the other Trojan women wailed aloud,'),(9292,'but my soul  was glad, for already my heart was turned to go back to my home, and I groaned for the blindness that Aphrodite gave me, when she led me thither from my dear native land, forsaking my child and my bridal chamber, and my husband, a man who lacked nothing, whether in wisdom or in comeliness.” '),(9293,' Then fair-haired Menelaus answered her and said:'),(9294,'“Aye verily, all this, wife, hast thou spoken aright.'),(9295,'Ere now have I come to know the counsel and the mind of many warriors, and have travelled over the wide earth,'),(9296,'but never yet have mine eyes beheld such an one  as was Odysseus of the steadfast heart.'),(9297,'What a thing was this, too, which that mighty man wrought and endured in the carven horse, wherein all we chiefs of the Argives were sitting, bearing to the Trojans death and fate!'),(9298,'Then thou camest thither,'),(9299,'and it must be that thou wast bidden  by some god, who wished to grant glory to the Trojans,'),(9300,'and godlike Deiphobus followed thee on thy way. '),(9301,'Thrice didst thou go about the hollow ambush, trying it with thy touch, and thou didst name aloud the chieftains of the Danaans by their names, likening thy voice to the voices of the wives of all the Argives.'),(9302,' Now I and the son of Tydeus and goodly Odysseus sat there in the midst and heard how thou didst call,'),(9303,'and we two were eager to rise up and come forth, or else to answer straightway from within,'),(9304,'but Odysseus held us back and stayed us, despite our eagerness.'),(9305,' Then all the other sons of the Achaeans held their peace, but Anticlus alone was fain to speak and answer thee;'),(9306,'but Odysseus firmly closed his mouth with strong hands, and saved all the Achaeans,'),(9307,'and held him thus until Pallas Athena led thee away.”'),(9308,' Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(9309,'“Menelaus, son of Atreus, fostered of Zeus, leader of hosts, all the more grievous is it;'),(9310,'for in no wise did this ward off from him woeful destruction, nay, not though the heart within him had been of iron.'),(9311,'But come, send us to bed, that lulled now  by sweet sleep we may rest and take our joy.”'),(9312,'Thus he spoke, and Argive Helen bade her handmaids place bedsteads beneath the portico, and to lay on them fair purple blankets, and to spread there over coverlets, and on these to put fleecy cloaks for clothing.'),(9313,' But the maids went forth from the hall with torches in their hands and strewed the couch,'),(9314,'and a herald led forth the guests.'),(9315,'So they slept there in the fore-hall of the palace, the prince Telemachus and the glorious son of Nestor;'),(9316,'but the son of Atreus slept in the inmost chamber of the lofty house,  and beside him lay long-robed Helen, peerless among women.'),(9317,'So soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, up from his bed arose Menelaus, good at the war-cry, and put on his clothing. About his shoulders he slung his sharp sword, and beneath his shining feet bound his fair sandals,  and went forth from his chamber like unto a god to look upon. Then he sat down beside Telemachus, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(9318,'“What need has brought thee hither, prince Telemachus, to goodly Lacedaemon over the broad back of the sea?'),(9319,'Tell me the truth of this.” '),(9320,'Tell me the truth of this.” '),(9321,' Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(9322,'“Menelaus, son of Atreus, fostered of Zeus, leader of hosts, I came if haply thou mightest tell me some tidings of my father.'),(9323,'My home is being devoured and my rich lands are ruined; with men that are foes my house is filled, who are ever  slaying my thronging sheep and my sleek kine of shambling gait, even the wooers of my mother, overweening in their insolence.'),(9324,'Therefore am I now come to thy knees, if perchance thou wilt be willing to tell me of his woeful death, whether thou sawest it haply with thine own eyes, or didst hear from some other the story  of his wanderings;'),(9325,'for beyond all men did his mother bear him to sorrow.'),(9326,'And do thou no wise out of ruth or pity for me speak soothing words, but tell me truly how thou didst come to behold him.'),(9327,'I beseech thee, if ever my father, noble Odysseus, promised aught to thee of word or deed and fulfilled it  in the land of the Trojans, where you Achaeans suffered woes, be mindful of it now, I pray thee, and tell me the truth.”'),(9328,'Then, stirred to sore displeasure, fair-haired Menelaus spoke to him:'),(9329,'“Out upon them, for verily in the bed of a man of valiant heart were they fain to lie, who are themselves cravens.'),(9330,' Even as when in the thicket-lair of a mighty lion a hind has laid to sleep her new-born suckling fawns, and roams over the mountain slopes and grassy vales seeking pasture, and then the lion comes to his lair and upon the two lets loose a cruel doom,  so will Odysseus let loose a cruel doom upon these men.'),(9331,'I would, O father Zeus and Athena and Apollo, that in such strength as when once in fair-stablished Lesbos he rose up and wrestled a match with Philomeleides and threw him mightily, and all the Achaeans rejoiced,  even in such strength Odysseus might come among the wooers;'),(9332,'then should they all find swift destruction and bitterness in their wooing. '),(9333,'But in this matter of which thou dost ask and beseech me, verily I will not swerve aside to speak of other things, nor will I deceive thee; but of all that the unerring old man of the sea told me. '),(9334,'“In Egypt, eager though I was to journey hither, the gods still held me back, because I offered not to them hecatombs that bring fulfillment,'),(9335,'and the gods ever wished that men should be mindful of their commands.'),(9336,'Now there is an island in the surging sea  in front of Egypt, and men call it Pharos, distant as far as a hollow ship runs in a whole day when the shrill wind blows fair behind her.'),(9337,'Therein is a harbor with good anchorage, whence men launch the shapely ships into the sea, when they have drawn supplies of black water.'),(9338,' There for twenty days the gods kept me, nor ever did the winds that blow over the deep spring up, which speed men\'s ships over the broad back of the sea.'),(9339,'And now would all my stores have been spent and the strength of my men, had not one of the gods taken pity on me and saved me, even Eidothea,  daughter of mighty Proteus, the old man of the sea; '),(9340,'for her heart above all others had I moved.'),(9341,'She met me as I wandered alone apart from my comrades,'),(9342,'who were ever roaming about the island, fishing with bent hooks, for hunger pinched their bellies;'),(9343,' and she came close to me, and spoke, and said:'),(9344,'“‘Art thou so very foolish, stranger, and slack of wit, or art thou of thine own will remiss, and hast pleasure in suffering woes?'),(9345,'So long art thou pent in the isle and canst find no sign of deliverance and the heart of thy comrades grows faint.’'),(9346,' “So she spoke, and I made answer and said: '),(9347,'‘I will speak out and tell thee, whosoever among goddesses thou art, that in no wise am I pent here of mine own will, but it must be that I have sinned against the immortals, who hold broad heaven.'),(9348,'But do thou tell me—for the gods know all things—  who of the immortals fetters me here, and has hindered me from my path, and tell me of my return, how I may go over the teeming deep.’'),(9349,'“So I spoke, and the beautiful goddess straightway made answer:'),(9350,'‘Then verily, stranger, will I frankly tell thee all. '),(9351,'There is wont to come hither the unerring old man of the sea,  immortal Proteus of Egypt, who knows the depths of every sea, and is the servant of Poseidon.'),(9352,'He, they say, is my father that begat me. '),(9353,'If thou couldst in any wise lie in wait and catch him, he will tell thee thy way and the measure of thy path,  and of thy return, how thou mayest go over the teeming deep.'),(9354,'Aye, and he will tell thee, thou fostered of Zeus, if so thou wilt, what evil and what good has been wrought in thy halls, while thou hast been gone on thy long and grievous way.’'),(9355,'“So she spoke, and I made answer and said: '),(9356,' ‘Do thou thyself now devise a means of lying in wait for the divine old man, lest haply he see me beforehand and being ware of my purpose avoid me.'),(9357,' For hard is a god for a mortal man to master.’ '),(9358,' \n“So I spoke, and the beautiful goddess straightway made answer:'),(9359,' ‘Then verily, stranger, will I frankly tell thee all.'),(9360,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 4.400-4.403'),(9361,'and around him the seals, the brood of the fair daughter of the sea,  sleep in a herd, coming forth from the gray water, and bitter is the smell they breathe of the depths of the sea.'),(9362,'Thither will I lead thee at break of day and lay you all in a row;'),(9363,'for do thou choose carefully three of thy companions, who are the best thou hast in thy well-benched ships.'),(9364,' And I will tell thee all the wizard wiles of that old man. '),(9365,'First he will count the seals, and go over them;'),(9366,'but when he has told them all off by fives, and beheld them, he will lay himself down in their midst, as a shepherd among his flocks of sheep.'),(9367,'Now so soon as you see him laid to rest,  thereafter let your hearts be filled with strength and courage, and do you hold him there despite his striving and struggling to escape.'),(9368,'For try he will, and will assume all manner of shapes of all things that move upon the earth, and of water, and of wondrous blazing fire.'),(9369,'Yet do ye hold him unflinchingly and grip him yet the more. '),(9370,' But when at length of his own will he speaks and questions thee in that shape in which you saw him laid to rest, then, hero, stay thy might, and set the old man free, and ask him who of the gods is wroth with thee, and of thy return, how thou mayest go over the teeming deep.’'),(9371,' “So saying she plunged beneath the surging sea,'),(9372,'but I went to my ships, where they stood on the sand,'),(9373,'and many things did my heart darkly ponder as I went.'),(9374,'But when I had come down to the ship and to the sea, and we had made ready our supper, and immortal night had come on,'),(9375,' then we lay down to rest on the shore of the sea.'),(9376,'And as soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, I went along the shore of the broad-wayed sea, praying earnestly to the gods; '),(9377,'and I took with me three of my comrades, in whom I trusted most for every adventure. '),(9378,' “She meanwhile had plunged beneath the broad bosom of the sea, and had brought forth from the deep the skins of four seals,'),(9379,'and she devised a plot against her father.'),(9380,'and she devised a plot against her father.'),(9381,'She had scooped out lairs in the sand of the sea, and sat waiting;'),(9382,'and we came very near to her, '),(9383,' and she made us to lie down in a row, and cast a skin over each.'),(9384,'Then would our ambush have proved most terrible,'),(9385,'for terribly did the deadly stench of the brine-bred seals distress us—'),(9386,' who would lay him down by a beast of the sea?—'),(9387,'but she of herself delivered us, and devised a great boon; '),(9388,' she brought and placed ambrosia of a very sweet fragrance beneath each man\'s nose, and destroyed the stench of the beast.'),(9389,'So all the morning we waited with steadfast heart,'),(9390,'and the seals came forth from the sea in throngs.'),(9391,'These then laid them down in rows along the shore of the sea,'),(9392,' and at noon the old man came forth from the sea and found the fatted seals; and he went over all, and counted their number.'),(9393,'Among the creatures he counted us first, nor did his heart guess that there was guile;'),(9394,'and then he too laid him down. '),(9395,'Thereat we rushed upon him with a shout, and  threw our arms about him,'),(9396,'nor did that old man forget his crafty wiles. Nay, at the first he turned into a bearded lion, and then into a serpent, and a leopard, and a huge boar; '),(9397,'then he turned into flowing water, and into a tree, high and leafy;'),(9398,'but we held on unflinchingly with steadfast heart.'),(9399,' But when at last that old man, skilled in wizard arts, grew weary, then he questioned me, and spoke, and said:'),(9400,'“‘Who of the gods, son of Atreus, took counsel with thee that thou mightest lie in wait for me, and take me against my will?'),(9401,'Of what hast thou need?’'),(9402,'“So he spoke, and I made answer, and said:'),(9403,'  ‘Thou knowest, old man—why dost thou seek to put me off with this question?—'),(9404,'how long a time I am pent in this isle, and can find no sign of deliverance, and my heart grows faint within me.'),(9405,' But do thou tell me—for the gods know all things—who of the immortals fetters me here, and has hindered me from my path, and tell me  of my return, how I may go over the teeming deep.’'),(9406,'“So I spoke, and he straightway made answer, and said:'),(9407,' ‘Nay, surely thou oughtest to have made fair offerings to Zeus and the other gods before embarking, that with greatest speed thou mightest have come to thy country, sailing over the wine-dark sea.'),(9408,'  For it is not thy fate to see thy friends, and reach thy well-built house and thy native land, before that thou hast once more gone to the waters of Aegyptus, the heaven-fed river,'),(9409,' and hast offered holy hecatombs to the immortal gods who hold broad heaven. '),(9410,' \n“So he spoke, and my spirit was broken within me, for that he bade me go again over the misty deep to Aegyptus, a long and weary way.'),(9411,' Yet even so I made answer, and said:'),(9412,' “‘All this will I perform, old man, even as thou dost bid.'),(9413,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 4.486-4.490'),(9414,'“So I spoke, and he straightway made answer, and said: '),(9415,'‘Son of Atreus, why dost thou question me of this?'),(9416,'In no wise does it behove thee to know, or to learn my mind;'),(9417,'nor, methinks, wilt thou long be free from tears, when thou hast heard all aright.'),(9418,' For many of them were slain, and many were left;'),(9419,'but two chieftains alone of the brazen-coated Achaeans perished on their homeward way '),(9420,'（ as for the fighting, thou thyself wast there）,'),(9421,'and one, I ween, still lives, and is held back on the broad deep.'),(9422,'“‘Aias truly was lost amid his long-oared ships.'),(9423,' Upon the great rocks of Gyrae Poseidon at first drove him, but saved him from the sea;'),(9424,'and he would have escaped his doom, hated of Athena though he was, had he not uttered a boastful word in great blindness of heart.'),(9425,'He declared that it was in spite of the gods that he had escaped the great gulf of the sea; '),(9426,' and Poseidon heard his boastful speech,'),(9427,'and straightway took his trident in his mighty hands, and smote the rock of Gyrae and clove it in sunder.'),(9428,'And one part abode in its place, but the sundered part fell into the sea, even that on which Aias sat at the first when his heart was greatly blinded,'),(9429,' and it bore him down into the boundless surging deep.'),(9430,'So there he perished, when he had drunk the salt water. '),(9431,' \n“‘But thy brother escaped, indeed, the fates and shunned them with his hollow ships,'),(9432,'for queenly Hera saved him.'),(9433,'But when he was now about  to reach the steep height of Malea, then the storm-wind caught him up and bore him over the teeming deep, groaning heavily, to the border of the land, where aforetime Thyestes dwelt, but where now dwelt Thyestes\' son Aegisthus.'),(9434,'But when from hence too a safe return was shewed him,  and the gods changed the course of the wind that it blew fair, and they reached home, then verily with rejoicing did Agamemnon set foot on his native land, and he clasped his land and kissed it,'),(9435,'and many were the hot tears that streamed from his eyes, for welcome to him was the sight of his land.'),(9436,'Now from his place of watch a watchman saw him, whom  guileful Aegisthus took and set there, promising him as a reward two talents of gold;'),(9437,'and he had been keeping guard for a year, lest Agamemnon should pass by him unseen, and be mindful of his furious might.'),(9438,'So he went to the palace to bear the tidings to the shepherd of the people,'),(9439,'and Aegisthus straightway planned a treacherous device.'),(9440,' He chose out twenty men, the best in the land, and set them to lie in wait, but on the further side of the hall he bade prepare a feast. '),(9441,'Then he went with chariot and horses to summon Agamemnon, shepherd of the people, his mind pondering a dastardly deed.'),(9442,'So he brought him up all unaware of his doom,  and when he had feasted him he slew him, as one slays an ox at the stall.'),(9443,'And not one of the comrades of the son of Atreus was left, of all that followed him, nor one of the men of Aegisthus, but they were all slain in the halls.’'),(9444,'“So he spoke, and my spirit was broken within me, and I wept, as I sat on the sands, nor had my heart  any longer desire to live and to behold the light of the sun.'),(9445,'But when I had had my fill of weeping and writhing, then the unerring old man of the sea said to me:'),(9446,'“‘No more, son of Atreus, do thou weep long time thus without ceasing, for in it we shall find no help.'),(9447,'Nay, rather, with all the speed thou canst,  strive that thou mayest come to thy native land, '),(9448,'for either thou wilt find Aegisthus alive, or haply Orestes may have forestalled thee and slain him, and thou mayest chance upon his funeral feast.’'),(9449,'“So he spoke, and my heart and spirit were again warmed with comfort in my breast despite my grief,  and I spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(9450,'“‘Of these men now I know,'),(9451,'but do thou name the third, who he is that still lives, and is held back upon the broad sea, or is haply dead. '),(9452,' Fain would I hear, despite my grief.’ '),(9453,' \n“So I spoke, and he straightway made answer, and said:'),(9454,'  ‘It is the son of Laertes, whose home is in Ithaca.'),(9455,'Him I saw in an island, shedding big tears, in the halls of the nymph Calypso, who keeps him there perforce,'),(9456,'and he cannot come to his native land,'),(9457,'for he has at hand no ships with oars and no comrades  to send him on his way over the broad back of the sea.'),(9458,'But for thyself, Menelaus, fostered of Zeus, it is not ordained that thou shouldst die and meet thy fate in horse-pasturing Argos, but to the Elysian plain and the bounds of the earth will the immortals convey thee, where dwells fair-haired Rhadamanthus,  and where life is easiest for men.'),(9459,'No snow is there, nor heavy storm, nor ever rain, but ever does Ocean send up blasts of the shrill-blowing West Wind that they may give cooling to men;'),(9460,'for thou hast Helen to wife, and art in their eyes the husband of the daughter of Zeus.’'),(9461,' “So saying he plunged beneath the surging sea, '),(9462,'but I went to my ships with my god like comrades, and many things did my heart darkly ponder as I went. '),(9463,'But when I had come down to the ship and to the sea, and we had made ready our supper, and immortal night had come on,  then we lay down to rest on the shore of the sea.'),(9464,'And as soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, our ships first of all we drew down to the bright sea, and set the masts and the sails in the shapely ships, and the men, too, went on board and sat down upon the benches,'),(9465,' and sitting well in order smote the grey sea with their oars.'),(9466,'So back again to the waters of Aegyptus, the heaven-fed river, I sailed, and there moored my ships and offered hecatombs that bring fulfillment. '),(9467,'But when I had stayed the wrath of the gods that are forever, I heaped up a mound to Agamemnon, that his fame might be unquenchable.'),(9468,' Then, when I had made an end of this, I set out for home, and the immortals gave me a fair wind, and brought me swiftly to my dear native land.'),(9469,'But come now, tarry in my halls until the eleventh or the twelfth day be come.'),(9470,'Then will I send thee forth with honor and give thee splendid gifts,  three horses and a well-polished car;'),(9471,'and besides I will give thee a beautiful cup, that thou mayest pour libations to the immortal gods, and remember me all thy days.” '),(9472,' \nThen wise Telemachus answered him:'),(9473,' “Son of Atreus, keep me no long time here,  '),(9474,' for verily for a year would I be content to sit in thy house, nor would desire for home or parents come upon me; '),(9475,'for wondrous is the pleasure I take in listening to thy tales and thy speech.'),(9476,' But even now my comrades are chafing in sacred Pylos, '),(9477,'and thou art keeping me long time here.'),(9478,' And whatsoever gift thou wouldest give me, let it be some treasure;'),(9479,'but horses will I not take to Ithaca, but will leave them here for thyself to delight in, '),(9480,' for thou art lord of a wide plain, wherein is lotus in abundance, and galingale and wheat and spelt, and broad-eared white barley.'),(9481,'  But in Ithaca there are no widespread courses nor aught of meadow-land.'),(9482,'It is a pasture-land of goats and pleasanter than one that pastures horses.'),(9483,'For not one of the islands that lean upon the sea is fit for driving horses, or rich in meadows,'),(9484,' and Ithaca least of all.”'),(9485,'So he spoke, and Menelaus, good at the war-cry, smiled,  and stroked him with his hand, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(9486,'“Thou art of noble blood, dear child, that thou speakest thus.'),(9487,'for well I may.'),(9488,'for well I may.'),(9489,'Of all the gifts that lie stored as treasures in my house, I will give thee that one which is fairest and costliest.'),(9490,' I will give thee a well-wrought mixing bowl.'),(9491,'All of silver it is, and with gold are the rims thereof gilded, the work of Hephaestus;'),(9492,'and the warrior Phaedimus, king of the Sidonians, gave it me, when his house sheltered me as I came thither, '),(9493,'and now I am minded to give it to thee.”'),(9494,' Thus they spoke to one another, and meanwhile the banqueters came to the palace of the divine king.'),(9495,'They drove up sheep, and brought strengthening wine,'),(9496,' and their wives with beautiful veils sent them bread.'),(9497,'Thus they were busied about the feast in the halls. '),(9498,' \n  \n\n\n======================================================================\nk1k1\n======================================================================\n But the wooers in front of the palace of Odysseus were making merry, throwing the discus and the javelin in a levelled place, as their wont was, in insolence of heart;'),(9499,'and Antinous and godlike Eurymachus were sitting there, the leaders of the wooers, who in valiance were far the best of all. '),(9500,' To them Noemon, son of Phronius, drew near, and he questioned Antinous, and spoke, and said:'),(9501,'“Antinous, know we at all in our hearts, or know we not, when Telemachus will return from sandy Pylos?'),(9502,'He is gone, taking a ship of mine,'),(9503,' and I have need of her  to cross over to spacious Elis, where I have twelve brood mares, and at the teat sturdy mules as yet unbroken.'),(9504,'Of these I would fain drive one off and break him in.”'),(9505,'So he spoke, and they marvelled at heart,'),(9506,'for they did not deem that Telemachus had gone to Neleian Pylos, but that he was somewhere there  on his lands, among the flocks or with the swineherd.'),(9507,'Then Antinous, son of Eupeithes, spoke to him, saying: '),(9508,'“Tell me the truth; when did he go, and what youths went with him?'),(9509,'Were they chosen youths of Ithaca, or hirelings and slaves of his own?'),(9510,'Able would he be to accomplish even that.'),(9511,' And tell me this truly, that I may know full well. Was it perforce and against thy will that he took from thee the black ship? or didst thou give it him freely of thine own will, because he besought thee?”'),(9512,'Then Noemon, son of Phronius, answered him:'),(9513,'“I myself freely gave it him.'),(9514,'What else could any man do,  when a man like him, his heart laden with care, makes entreaty?'),(9515,'Hard it were to deny the gift.'),(9516,'The youths that are the noblest in the land after ourselves, even these have gone with him;'),(9517,'and among them I noted one going on board as their leader, Mentor, or a god, who was in all things like unto Mentor.'),(9518,' But at this I marvel. '),(9519,'I saw goodly Mentor here yesterday at early dawn; but at that time he embarked for Pylos.”'),(9520,'So saying he departed to his father\'s house, but of those two the proud hearts were angered.'),(9521,'The wooers they straightway made to sit down and cease from their games;'),(9522,' and among them spoke Antinous, son of Eupeithes, in displeasure;'),(9523,'and with rage was his black heart wholly filled, and his eyes were like blazing fire.'),(9524,'“Out upon him, verily a proud deed has been insolently brought to pass by Telemachus, even this journey,'),(9525,' and we deemed that he would never see it accomplished.'),(9526,' Forth in despite of all of us here the lad is gone without more ado, launching a ship, and choosing the best men in the land. and we deemed that he would never see it accomplished.'),(9527,' He will begin by and by to be our bane; '),(9528,'but to his own undoing may Zeus destroy his might before ever he reaches the measure of manhood.'),(9529,'But come, give me a swift ship and twenty men,  that I may watch in ambush for him as he passes in the strait between Ithaca and rugged Samos. Thus shall his voyaging in search of his father come to a sorry end.”'),(9530,'So he spoke, and they all praised his words, and bade him act.'),(9531,' And straightway they rose up and went to the house of Odysseus. '),(9532,' Now Penelope was no long time without knowledge of the plans which the wooers were plotting in the deep of their hearts; '),(9533,'for the herald Medon told her, who heard their counsel as he stood without the court '),(9534,'and they within were weaving their plot.'),(9535,'So he went through the hall to bear the tidings to Penelope;'),(9536,' and as he stepped across the threshold Penelope spoke to him and said:'),(9537,'“Herald, why have the lordly wooers sent thee forth?'),(9538,'Was it to tell the handmaids of divine Odysseus to cease from their tasks, and make ready a feast for them?'),(9539,'Never wooing any more, nor consorting together elsewhere,  may they now feast here their latest and their last—'),(9540,'even ye who are ever thronging here and wasting much livelihood, the wealth of wise Telemachus.'),(9541,' Surely ye hearkened not at all in olden days, when ye were children, when your fathers told what manner of man Odysseus was among them that begat you,  in that he wrought no wrong in deed or word to any man in the land, as the wont is of divine kings—'),(9542,'one man they hate and another they love.'),(9543,'Yet he never wrought iniquity at all to any man.'),(9544,'But your mind and your unseemly deeds  are plain to see, nor is there in after days any gratitude for good deeds done.”'),(9545,'Then Medon, wise of heart, answered her: '),(9546,'“I would, O queen, that this were the greatest evil.'),(9547,'But another greater far and more grievous are the wooers planning, which I pray that the son of Cronos may never bring to pass. '),(9548,'  They are minded to slay Telemachus with the sharp sword on his homeward way;'),(9549,'for he went in quest of tidings of his father to sacred Pylos and to goodly Lacedaemon.”'),(9550,'So he spoke, and her knees were loosened where she sat, and her heart melted. Long time she was speechless,'),(9551,'and both her eyes  were filled with tears, and the flow of her voice was checked.'),(9552,'But at last she made answer, and said to him:'),(9553,'“Herald, why is my son gone? '),(9554,'He had no need to go on board swift-faring ships, which serve men as horses of the deep, and cross over the wide waters of the sea.'),(9555,' Was it that not even his name should be left among men?”'),(9556,'Then Medon, wise of heart, answered her: '),(9557,'“I know not whether some god impelled him, or whether his own heart was moved to go to Pylos, that he might learn either of his father\'s return or what fate he had met.” '),(9558,' So he spoke, and departed through the house of Odysseus,'),(9559,'and on her fell a cloud of soul-consuming grief, and she had no more the heart to sit upon one of the many seats that were in the room, but down upon the threshold of her fair-wrought chamber she sank, moaning piteously,'),(9560,'and round about her wailed her handmaids,  even all that were in the house, both young and old.'),(9561,'Among these with sobs of lamentation spoke Penelope:'),(9562,'“Hear me, my friends,'),(9563,'for to me the Olympian has given sorrow above all the women who were bred and born with me.'),(9564,'For long since I lost my noble husband of the lion heart,  pre-eminent in all manner of worth among the Danaans, my noble husband, whose fame is wide through Hellas and mid-Argos.'),(9565,'And now again my well-loved son have the storm-winds swept away from our halls without tidings, nor did I hear of his setting forth. '),(9566,'Cruel, that ye are! Not even you took thought, any one of you,  to rouse me from my couch, though in your hearts ye knew full well when he went on board the hollow black ship. '),(9567,'For had I learned that he was pondering this journey, he should verily have stayed here, how eager soever to be gone, or he should have left me dead in the halls.'),(9568,' But now let one hasten to call hither the aged Dolius, my servant, whom my father gave me or ever I came hither, and who keeps my garden of many trees, that he may straightway go and sit by Laertes, and tell him of all these things. So haply may Laertes weave some plan in his heart,  and go forth and with weeping make his plea to the people, who are minded to destroy his race and that of godlike Odysseus.”'),(9569,'Then the good nurse Eurycleia answered her:'),(9570,'“Dear lady, thou mayest verily slay me with the pitiless sword or let me abide in the house, '),(9571,'yet will I not hide my word from thee. '),(9572,' I knew all this, and gave him whatever he bade me, bread and sweet wine. '),(9573,'But he took from me a mighty oath not to tell thee until at least the twelfth day should come, or thou shouldst thyself miss him and hear that he was gone, that thou mightest not mar thy fair flesh with weeping. '),(9574,' But now bathe thyself, and take clean raiment for thy body, and then go up to thy upper chamber with thy handmaids and pray to Athena, the daughter of Zeus who bears the aegis;'),(9575,'for she may then save him even from death.'),(9576,'And trouble not a troubled old man;'),(9577,'for  the race of the son of Arceisius is not, methinks, utterly hated by the blessed gods, but there shall still be one, I ween, to hold the high-roofed halls and the rich fields far away.” '),(9578,'So she spoke, and lulled Penelope\'s laments, and made her eyes to cease from weeping.'),(9579,' She then bathed, and took clean raiment for her body,  and went up to her upper chamber with her handmaids, and placing barley grains in a basket prayed to Athena:'),(9580,'\n“Hear me, child of Zeus who bears the aegis, unwearied one. If ever Odysseus, of many wiles, burnt to thee in his halls fat thigh-pieces of heifer or ewe,  remember these things now, I pray thee, and save my dear son, and ward off from him the wooers in their evil insolence.”'),(9581,'\nSo saying she raised the sacred cry, and the goddess heard her prayer. '),(9582,'\nBut the wooers broke into uproar throughout the shadowy halls,'),(9583,'and thus would one of the proud youths speak:'),(9584,' “Aye, verily the queen, wooed of many, is preparing our marriage, nor does she know at all that death has been made ready for her son.”'),(9585,'So would one of them speak; but they knew not how these things were to be. '),(9586,'And Antinous addressed their company, and said:'),(9587,'“Good sirs, shun haughty speech  of every kind alike, lest someone report your speech even within the house. '),(9588,'Nay come, in silence thus let us arise and put into effect our plan which pleased us one and all at heart.”'),(9589,'So he spoke, and chose twenty men that were best, and they went their way to the swift ship and the shore of the sea.'),(9590,' The ship first of all they drew down to the deep water, and set the mast and sail in the black ship, and fitted the oars in the leathern thole-straps, all in due order, and spread the white sail.'),(9591,'And proud squires brought them their weapons.'),(9592,' Well out in the roadstead they moored the ship, and themselves disembarked.'),(9593,'There then they took supper, and waited till evening should come.'),(9594,'But she, the wise Penelope, lay there in her upper chamber, touching no food, tasting neither meat nor drink, pondering whether her peerless son would escape death,  or be slain by the insolent wooers.'),(9595,'And even as a lion is seized with fear and broods amid a throng of men, when they draw their crafty ring about him, so was she pondering when sweet sleep came upon her.'),(9596,'And she sank back and slept, and all her joints relaxed. '),(9597,' Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, took other counsel. '),(9598,'She made a phantom, and likened it in form to a woman, Iphthime, daughter of great-hearted Icarius, whom Eumelus wedded, whose home was in Pherae.'),(9599,'And she sent it to the house of divine Odysseus,  to Penelope in the midst of her wailing and lamenting, to bid her cease from weeping and tearful lamentation.'),(9600,'So into the chamber it passed by the thong of the bolt, and stood above her head, and spoke to her, and said:'),(9601,'“Sleepest thou, Penelope, thy heart sore stricken? '),(9602,' Nay, the gods that live at ease suffer thee not to weep or be distressed, seeing that thy son is yet to return;'),(9603,'for in no wise is he a sinner in the eyes of the gods.”'),(9604,'Then wise Penelope answered her, as she slumbered very sweetly at the gates of dreams:'),(9605,' “Why, sister, art thou come hither? '),(9606,'Thou hast not heretofore been wont to come, for thou dwellest in a home far away.'),(9607,'And thou biddest me cease from my grief and the many pains that distress me in mind and heart. Long since I lost my noble husband of the lion heart,  pre-eminent in all manner of worth among the Danaans, my noble husband whose fame is wide in Hellas and mid-Argos.'),(9608,'And now again my well-loved son is gone forth in a hollow ship, a mere child, knowing naught of toils and the gatherings of men.'),(9609,'For him I sorrow even more than for that other,'),(9610,' and tremble for him, and fear lest aught befall him, whether it be in the land of the men to whom he is gone, or on the sea.'),(9611,'For many foes are plotting against him, eager to slay him before he comes back to his native land.”'),(9612,'Then the dim phantom answered her, and said:'),(9613,' “Take heart, and be not in thy mind too sore afraid;'),(9614,'since such a guide goes with him as men have full often besought to stand by their side, for she has power,—even Pallas Athena.'),(9615,'And she pities thee in thy sorrow,'),(9616,'for she it is that has sent me forth to tell thee this.”'),(9617,' Then again wise Penelope answered her:'),(9618,' “If thou art indeed a god, and hast listened to the voice of a god, come, tell me, I pray thee, also of that hapless one, whether he still lives and beholds the light of the sun, or whether he is already dead and in the house of Hades.”'),(9619,' And the dim phantom answered her, and said:'),(9620,'“Nay, of him I may not speak at length, whether he be alive or dead;'),(9621,'it is an ill thing to speak words vain as wind.”'),(9622,'So saying the phantom glided away by the bolt of the door into the breath of the winds. '),(9623,'And  the daughter of Icarius started up from sleep,'),(9624,'and her heart was warmed with comfort, that so clear a vision had sped to her in the darkness of night.'),(9625,'But the wooers embarked, and sailed over the watery ways, pondering in their hearts utter murder for Telemachus. '),(9626,'There is a rocky isle in the midst of the sea,  midway between Ithaca and rugged Samos, Asteris, of no great size,'),(9627,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 4.846-4'),(9628,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 4'),(9629,' Now Dawn arose from her couch from beside lordly Tithonus, to bear light to the immortals and to mortal men.'),(9630,' And the gods were sitting down to council, and among them Zeus, who thunders on high, whose might is supreme.'),(9631,'  To them Athena was recounting the many woes of Odysseus, as she called them to mind; '),(9632,'for it troubled her that he abode in the dwelling of the nymph:'),(9633,'\n“Father Zeus, and ye other blessed gods that are forever, never henceforward let sceptred king with a ready heart be kind and gentle, nor let him heed righteousness in his mind;  but let him ever be harsh, and work unrighteousness,'),(9634,'seeing that no one remembers divine Odysseus of the people whose lord he was; yet gentle was he as a father.'),(9635,' He verily abides in an island suffering grievous pains, in the halls of the nymph Calypso, who  keeps him perforce; '),(9636,' and he cannot return to his own land, '),(9637,'for he has at hand no ships with oars and no comrades to send him on his way over the broad back of the sea.'),(9638,' And now again they are minded to slay his well-loved son on his homeward way; '),(9639,'for he went in quest of tidings of his father  to sacred Pylos and to goodly Lacedaemon.”'),(9640,'Then Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, answered her, and said:'),(9641,' “My child, what a word has escaped the barrier of thy teeth!'),(9642,' Didst thou not thyself devise this plan, that verily Odysseus might take vengeance on these men at his coming?'),(9643,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 5.25-5.27'),(9644,'  But concerning Telemachus, do thou guide him in thy wisdom, for thou canst, that all unscathed he may reach his native land, and the wooers may come back in their ship ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 25 to line 27'),(9645,'He spoke, and said to Hermes, his dear son:'),(9646,'“Hermes, do thou now, seeing that thou art at other times our messenger,  declare to the fair-tressed nymph our fixed resolve, even the return of Odysseus of the steadfast heart, that he may return with guidance neither of gods nor of mortal men, '),(9647,' but that on a stoutly-bound raft, suffering woes, he may come on the twentieth day to deep-soiled Scheria,  the land of the Phaeacians, who are near of kin to the gods. These shall heartily shew him all honor, as if he were a god, and shall send him in a ship to his dear native land, after giving him stores of bronze and gold and raiment, more than Odysseus would ever have won for himself from Troy,  if he had returned unscathed with his due share of the spoil. '),(9648,'For in this wise it is his fate to see his friends, and reach his high-roofed house and his native land.”'),(9649,'So he spoke, and the messenger, Argeiphontes, failed not to hearken.  '),(9650,'Straightway he bound beneath his feet his beautiful sandals,  immortal, golden, which were wont to bear him over the waters of the sea and over the boundless land swift as the blasts of the wind.'),(9651,' And he took the wand wherewith he lulls to sleep the eyes of whom he will, while others again he awakens even out of slumber.'),(9652,' With this in his hand the strong Argeiphontes flew. '),(9653,'   On to Pieria he stepped from the upper air, and swooped down upon the sea, '),(9654,'and then sped over the wave like a bird, the cormorant, which in quest of fish over the dread gulfs of the unresting sea wets its thick plumage in the brine.'),(9655,' In such wise did Hermes ride upon the multitudinous waves.'),(9656,'  But when he had reached the island which lay afar, then forth from the violet sea he came to land, and went his way until he came to a great cave, wherein dwelt the fair-tressed nymph; '),(9657,'and he found her within.'),(9658,' A great fire was burning on the hearth, and from afar over the isle there was a fragrance  of cleft cedar and juniper, as they burned; '),(9659,'but she within was singing with a sweet voice as she went to and fro before the loom, weaving with a golden shuttle.'),(9660,' Round about the cave grew a luxuriant wood, alder and poplar and sweet-smelling cypress, '),(9661,' wherein birds long of wing were wont to nest, owls and falcons and sea-crows with chattering tongues, who ply their business on the sea.'),(9662,' And right there about the hollow cave ran trailing a garden vine, in pride of its prime, richly laden with clusters.'),(9663,'  And fountains four in a row were flowing with bright water hard by one another, turned one this way, one that.'),(9664,' And round about soft meadows of violets and parsley were blooming.'),(9665,' There even an immortal, who chanced to come, might gaze and marvel, and delight his soul; '),(9666,' and there the messenger Argeiphontes stood and marvelled.'),(9667,' But when he had marvelled in his heart at all things, straightway he went into the wide cave;'),(9668,' nor did Calypso, the beautiful goddess, fail to know him, when she saw him face to face; '),(9669,'for not unknown are  the immortal gods to one another, even though one dwells in a home far away. '),(9670,'But the great-hearted Odysseus he found not within; for he sat weeping on the shore, as his wont had been, racking his soul with tears and groans and griefs, '),(9671,'and he would look over the unresting sea, shedding tears.'),(9672,'  And Calypso, the beautiful goddess, questioned Hermes, when she had made him sit on a bright shining chair:'),(9673,'\n“Why, pray, Hermes of the golden wand, hast thou come, an honorable guest and welcome?'),(9674,' heretofore thou hast not been wont to come.'),(9675,' Speak what is in thy mind; '),(9676,'my heart bids me fulfil it,  if fulfil it I can, and it is a thing that hath fulfillment.'),(9677,'But follow me further, that I may set before thee entertainment.” '),(9678,' \nSo saying, the goddess set before him a table laden with ambrosia, and mixed the ruddy nectar.'),(9679,' So he drank and ate, the messenger Argeiphontes.'),(9680,'  But when he had dined and satisfied his soul with food, then he made answer, and addressed her, saying:'),(9681,'\n“Thou, a goddess, dost question me, a god, upon my coming, '),(9682,'\nand I will speak my word truly,'),(9683,' since thou biddest me.'),(9684,' It was Zeus who bade me come hither against my will.'),(9685,'  Who of his own will would speed over so great space of salt sea-water, great past telling?'),(9686,' Nor is there at hand any city of mortals who offer to the gods sacrifice and choice hecatombs.'),(9687,' But it is in no wise possible for any other god to evade or make void the will of Zeus, who bears the aegis.'),(9688,'  He says that there is here with thee a man most wretched above all those warriors who around the city of Priam fought for nine years, and in the tenth year sacked the city and departed homeward.'),(9689,' But on the way they sinned against Athena, and she sent upon them an evil wind and long waves.'),(9690,'  There all the rest of his goodly comrades perished, but as for him, the wind and the wave, as they bore him, brought him hither.'),(9691,' Him now Zeus bids thee to send on his way with all speed, '),(9692,'for it is not his fate to perish here far from his friends, but it is still his lot to see his friends and reach  his high-roofed house and his native land.”'),(9693,'So he spoke, and Calypso, the beautiful goddess, shuddered, and she spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(9694,' “Cruel are ye, O ye gods, and quick to envy above all others, seeing that ye begrudge goddesses that they should mate with men  openly, if any takes a mortal as her dear bed-fellow. '),(9695,'Thus, when rosy-fingered Dawn took to herself Orion, ye gods that live at ease begrudged her, till in Ortygia chaste Artemis of the golden throne assailed him with her gentle shafts and slew him.'),(9696,'  Thus too, when fair-tressed Demeter, yielding to her passion, lay in love with Iasion in the thrice-ploughed fallow land, '),(9697,'Zeus was not long without knowledge thereof, but smote him with his bright thunder-bolt and slew him.'),(9698,' And even so again do ye now begrudge me, O ye gods, that a mortal man should abide with me.'),(9699,'  Him I saved when he was bestriding the keel and all alone, for Zeus had smitten his swift ship with his bright thunder-bolt, and had shattered it in the midst of the wine-dark sea.'),(9700,' There all the rest of his goodly comrades perished, but as for him, the wind and the wave, as they bore him, brought him hither.'),(9701,'  Him I welcomed kindly and gave him food, and said that I would make him immortal and ageless all his days.'),(9702,' But since it is in no wise possible for any other god to evade or make void the will of Zeus who bears the aegis, let him go his way, if Zeus thus orders and commands,  over the unresting sea. '),(9703,' But it is not I that shall give him convoy, '),(9704,'for I have at hand no ships with oars and no men to send him on his way over the broad back of the sea.'),(9705,' But with a ready heart will I give him counsel, and will hide naught, that all unscathed he may return to his native land.” '),(9706,' \n  Then again the messenger Argeiphontes answered her: '),(9707,'“Even so send him forth now, and beware of the wrath of Zeus, lest haply he wax wroth and visit his anger upon thee hereafter.\"'),(9708,'So saying, the strong Argeiphontes departed, '),(9709,' and the queenly nymph went to the great-hearted Odysseus,  when she had heard the message of Zeus.'),(9710,'Him she found sitting on the shore,'),(9711,' and his eyes were never dry of tears, and his sweet life was ebbing away, as he longed mournfully for his return, for the nymph was no longer pleasing in his sight.'),(9712,' By night indeed he would sleep by her side perforce  in the hollow caves, unwilling beside the willing nymph, '),(9713,'but by day he would sit on the rocks and the sands, racking his soul with tears and groans and griefs, and he would look over the unresting sea, shedding tears.'),(9714,' Then coming close to him, the beautiful goddess addressed him:'),(9715,'\n  “Unhappy man, sorrow no longer here, I pray thee, nor let thy life pine away; '),(9716,'\nfor even now with a ready heart will I send thee on thy way.'),(9717,' Nay, come, hew with the axe long beams, and make a broad raft, '),(9718,'and fasten upon it cross-planks for a deck well above it, that it may bear thee over the misty deep.'),(9719,'  And I will place therein bread and water and red wine to satisfy thy heart, to keep hunger from thee. And I will clothe thee with raiment,'),(9720,'  and will send a fair wind behind thee, that all unscathed thou mayest return to thy native land, if it be the will of the gods who hold broad heaven;  for they are mightier than I both to purpose and to fulfil.”'),(9721,'\nSo she spoke, and much-enduring goodly Odysseus shuddered, and he spoke, and addressed her with winged words:'),(9722,' “Some other thing, goddess, art thou planning in this, and not my sending, seeing that thou biddest me cross on a raft the great gulf of the sea,  dread and grievous, '),(9723,' over which not even the shapely, swift-faring ships pass, rejoicing in the wind of Zeus.'),(9724,' But I will not set foot on a raft in thy despite, unless thou, goddess, wilt bring thyself to swear a mighty oath that thou wilt not plot against me any fresh mischief to my hurt.”'),(9725,'  So he spoke, but Calypso, the beautiful goddess, smiled, and stroked him with her hand, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(9726,' “Verily thou art a knave, and not stunted in wit, that thou hast bethought thee to utter such a word. '),(9727,'Now therefore let earth be witness to this, and the broad heaven above,  and the down-flowing water of the Styx, which is the greatest and most dread oath for the blessed gods, that I will not plot against thee any fresh mischief to thy hurt.'),(9728,' Nay, I have such thoughts in mind, and will give such counsel, as I should devise for mine own self, if such need should come on me.'),(9729,'  For I too have a mind that is righteous, and the heart in this breast of mine is not of iron, but hath compassion.” '),(9730,' \nSo saying, the beautiful goddess led the way quickly, '),(9731,' \nand he followed in the footsteps of the goddess.'),(9732,' And they came to the hollow cave, the goddess and the man,  and he sat down upon the chair from which Hermes had arisen, and the nymph set before him all manner of food to eat and drink, of such sort as mortal men eat.'),(9733,' But she herself sat over against divine Odysseus, and before her the handmaids set ambrosia and nectar.'),(9734,' So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them. '),(9735,' But when they had their fill of food and drink, Calypso, the beautiful goddess, was the first to speak, and said:'),(9736,'\n“Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices,  would\'st thou then fare now forthwith home to thy dear native land! '),(9737,'Yet, even so fare thee well. '),(9738,'Howbeit if in thy heart thou knewest all the measure of woe it is thy fate to fulfil before thou comest to thy native land thou wouldest abide here and keep this house with me, and wouldest be immortal, for all thy desire to see  thy wife for whom thou longest day by day.'),(9739,'Surely not inferior to her do I declare myself to be either in form or stature, for in no wise is it seemly that mortal women should vie with immortals in form or comeliness.\"'),(9740,'\nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said:'),(9741,'  “Mighty goddess, be not wroth with me for this. '),(9742,'I know full well of myself that wise Penelope is meaner to look upon than thou in comeliness and in stature, '),(9743,'for she is a mortal, while thou art immortal and ageless.'),(9744,' But even so I wish and long day by day  to reach my home, and to see the day of my return. '),(9745,'And if again some god shall smite me on the wine-dark sea, I will endure it, having in my breast a heart that endures affliction.'),(9746,' For ere this I have suffered much and toiled much amid the waves and in war; '),(9747,'let this also be added unto that.\"'),(9748,'  So he spoke, and the sun set and darkness came on. '),(9749,'And the two went into the innermost recess of the hollow cave, and took their joy of love, abiding each by the other\'s side. '),(9750,' \nAs soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, straightway Odysseus put on a cloak and a tunic,  and the nymph clothed herself in a long white robe, finely woven and beautiful, and about her waist she cast a fair girdle of gold, and on her head a veil above.'),(9751,' Then she set herself to plan the sending of the great-hearted Odysseus.'),(9752,' She gave him a great axe, well fitted to his hands,  an axe of bronze, sharpened on both sides; '),(9753,'and in it was a beautiful handle of olive wood, securely fastened;'),(9754,'and thereafter she gave him a polished adze.'),(9755,' Then she led the way to the borders of the island where tall trees were standing, alder and popular and fir, reaching to the skies,  long dry and well-seasoned, which would float for him lightly. '),(9756,'But when she had shewn him where the tall trees grew, Calypso, the beautiful goddess, returned homewards, but he fell to cutting timbers, '),(9757,'and his work went forward apace.'),(9758,' Twenty trees in all did he fell, and trimmed them with the axe;  then he cunningly smoothed them all and made them straight to the line.'),(9759,' Meanwhile Calypso, the beautiful goddess, brought him augers;'),(9760,' and he bored all the pieces and fitted them to one another, and with pegs and morticings did he hammer it together. '),(9761,' Wide as a man well-skilled in carpentry marks out the curve of the hull of a freight-ship,  broad of beam, even so wide did Odysseus make his raft.'),(9762,' And he set up the deck-beams, bolting them to the close-set ribs, and laboured on; '),(9763,'and he finished the raft with long gunwales.'),(9764,' In it he set a mast and a yard-arm, fitted to it, '),(9765,' and furthermore made him a steering-oar, wherewith to steer.'),(9766,' Then he fenced in the whole from stem to stern with willow withes to be a defence against the wave,'),(9767,' and strewed much brush thereon.'),(9768,' Meanwhile Calypso, the beautiful goddess, brought him cloth to make him a sail,'),(9769,'and he fashioned that too with skill.'),(9770,'  And he made fast in the raft braces and halyards and sheets, and then with levers forced it down into the bright sea. '),(9771,' \nNow the fourth day came and all his work was done.'),(9772,' And on the fifth the beautiful Calypso sent him on his way from the island after she had bathed him and clothed him in fragrant raiment.'),(9773,'  On the raft the goddess put a skin of dark wine, and another, a great one, of water, and provisions, too, in a wallet.'),(9774,'Therein she put abundance of dainties to satisfy his heart,'),(9775,'  and she sent forth a gentle wind and warm.'),(9776,' Gladly then did goodly Odysseus spread his sail to the breeze; '),(9777,' and he sat and guided his raft skilfully with the steering-oar, nor did sleep fall upon his eyelids, as he watched the Pleiads, and late-setting Bootes, and the Bear, which men also call the Wain, which ever circles where it is and watches Orion,  and alone has no part in the baths of Ocean. '),(9778,' For this star Calypso, the beautiful goddess, had bidden him to keep on the left hand as he sailed over the sea.'),(9779,' For seventeen days then he sailed over the sea, and on the eighteenth appeared the shadowy mountains  of the land of the Phaeacians, where it lay nearest to him; '),(9780,'and it shewed like unto a shield in the misty deep.'),(9781,'\nBut the glorious Earth-shaker, as he came back from the Ethiopians, beheld him from afar, from the mountains of the Solymi:'),(9782,'for Odysseus was seen of him sailing over the sea;'),(9783,' and he waxed the more wroth in spirit,  and shook his head, and thus he spoke to his own heart:'),(9784,'\n“Out on it! Surely the gods have changed their purpose regarding Odysseus, while I was among the Ethiopians. And lo, he is near to the land of the Phaeacians, where it is his fate to escape from the great bonds of the woe which has come upon him.'),(9785,'  Aye, but even yet, methinks, I shall drive him to surfeit of evil.\"'),(9786,'So saying, he gathered the clouds, and seizing his trident in his hands troubled the sea,'),(9787,' and roused all blasts of all manner of winds, and hid with clouds land and sea alike; '),(9788,' and night rushed down from heaven. '),(9789,'  Together the East Wind and the South Wind dashed, and the fierce-blowing West Wind and the North Wind, born in the bright heaven, rolling before him a mighty wave. '),(9790,'Then were the knees of Odysseus loosened and his heart melted, and deeply moved he spoke to his own mighty spirit:'),(9791,'“Ah me, wretched that I am!  What is to befall me at the last?'),(9792,'  I fear me that verily all that the goddess said was true, when she declared that on the sea, before ever I came to my native land, I should fill up my measure of woes; '),(9793,'and lo, all this now is being brought to pass.'),(9794,' In such wise does Zeus overcast the broad heaven with clouds, and has stirred up the sea, and the blasts  of all manner of winds sweep upon me; '),(9795,'now is my utter destruction sure.'),(9796,' Thrice blessed those Danaans, aye, four times blessed, who of old perished in the wide land of Troy, doing the pleasure of the sons of Atreus.'),(9797,' Even so would that I had died and met my fate on that day when the throngs  of the Trojans hurled upon me bronze-tipped spears, fighting around the body of the dead son of Peleus. '),(9798,' Then should I have got funeral rites, and the Achaeans would have spread my fame, '),(9799,'but now by a miserable death was it appointed me to be cut off.” '),(9800,' \nEven as thus he spoke the great wave smote him from on high, rushing upon him with terrible might, and around it whirled his raft.'),(9801,'  Far from the raft he fell, and let fall the steering-oar from his hand; '),(9802,' but his mast was broken in the midst by the fierce blast of tumultuous winds that came upon it, and far in the sea sail and yardarm fell.'),(9803,' As for him, long time did the wave hold him in the depths, nor could he  rise at once from beneath the onrush of the mighty wave, '),(9804,'for the garments which beautiful Calypso had given him weighed him down.'),(9805,' At length, however, he came up, and spat forth from his mouth the bitter brine which flowed in streams from his head. '),(9806,'Yet even so he did not forget his raft, in evil case though he was,  but sprang after it amid the waves, and laid hold of it, and sat down in the midst of it, seeking to escape the doom of death; '),(9807,'and a great wave ever bore him this way and that along its course.'),(9808,' As when in autumn the North Wind bears the thistle-tufts over the plain, and close they cling to one another,  so did the winds bear the raft this way and that over the sea. '),(9809,'Now the South Wind would fling it to the North Wind to be driven on, and now again the East Wind would yield it to the West Wind to drive.'),(9810,'\nBut the daughter of Cadmus, Ino of the fair ankles, saw him, even Leucothea, who of old was a mortal of human speech,  but now in the deeps of the sea has won a share of honor from the gods. '),(9811,'\nShe was touched with pity for Odysseus, as he wandered and was in sore travail, and she rose up from the deep like a sea-mew on the wing, and sat on the stoutly-bound raft, and spoke, saying:'),(9812,'\n“Unhappy man, how is it that Poseidon, the earth-shaker,  has conceived such furious wrath against thee, that he is sowing for thee the seeds of many evils?'),(9813,'Yet verily he shall not utterly destroy thee for all his rage.'),(9814,'  Nay, do thou thus; and methinks thou dost not lack understanding.'),(9815,' Strip off these garments, and leave thy raft to be driven by the winds, but do thou swim with thy hands and so strive to reach  the land of the Phaeacians, where it is thy fate to escape.'),(9816,' Come, take this veil, and stretch it beneath thy breast.'),(9817,'It is immortal; there is no fear that thou shalt suffer aught or perish.'),(9818,'there is no fear that thou shalt suffer aught or perish. But when with thy hands thou hast laid hold of the land, loose it from thee, and cast it into the wine-dark sea  far from the land, and thyself turn away.”'),(9819,'\nSo saying, the goddess gave him the veil, and herself plunged again into the surging deep, like a sea-mew; '),(9820,'and the dark wave hid her.'),(9821,' Then the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus pondered,  and deeply moved he spoke to his own mighty spirit:'),(9822,'“Woe is me! Let it not be that some one of the immortals is again weaving a snare for me, that she bids me leave my raft.'),(9823,' Nay, but verily I will not yet obey, for afar off mine eyes beheld the land, where she said I was to escape.'),(9824,' But this will I do, and meseems that this is best: '),(9825,' as long as the timbers hold firm in their fastenings, so long will I remain here and endure to suffer affliction; '),(9826,'but when the wave shall have shattered the raft to pieces, I will swim, seeing that there is naught better to devise.” '),(9827,' \n  While he pondered thus in mind and heart, Poseidon, the earth-shaker, made to rise up a great wave, dread and grievous, arching over from above, and drove it upon him.'),(9828,' And as when a strong wind tosses a heap of straw that is dry,'),(9829,'and some it scatters here, some there, '),(9830,' even so the wave scattered the long timbers of the raft. '),(9831,'But Odysseus bestrode one plank, as though he were riding a horse, and stripped off the garments which beautiful Calypso had given him.'),(9832,' Then straightway he stretched the veil beneath his breast, and flung himself headlong into the sea with hands outstretched,  ready to swim.'),(9833,' And the lord, the earth-shaker, saw him, and he shook his head, and thus he spoke to his own heart:'),(9834,'\n“So now, after thou hast suffered many ills, go wandering over the deep, till thou comest among the folk fostered of Zeus.'),(9835,' Yet even so, methinks, thou shalt not make any mock at thy suffering.”'),(9836,'\n  So saying, he lashed his fair-maned horses, and came to Aegae, where is his glorious palace.'),(9837,'\nBut Athena, daughter of Zeus, took other counsel.'),(9838,' She stayed the paths of the other winds, and bade them all cease and be lulled to rest; '),(9839,' but she roused the swift North Wind, and broke the waves before him, to the end that Zeus-born Odysseus might come among the Phaeacians, lovers of the oar, escaping from death and the fates.'),(9840,'\nThen for two nights and two days he was driven about over the swollen waves, and full often his heart forboded destruction.'),(9841,'  But when fair-tressed Dawn brought to its birth the third day, then the wind ceased and there was a windless calm, '),(9842,' and he caught sight of the shore close at hand, casting a quick glance forward, as he was raised up by a great wave.'),(9843,'And even as when most welcome to his children appears the life  of a father who lies in sickness, bearing grievous pains, long while wasting away, and some cruel god assails him, but then to their joy the gods free him from his woe, so to Odysseus did the land and the wood seem welcome; and he swam on, eager to set foot on the land.'),(9844,'  But when he was as far away as a man\'s voice carries when he shouts, and heard the boom of the sea upon the reefs—'),(9845,'for the great wave thundered against the dry land, belching upon it in terrible fashion, and all things were wrapped in the foam of the sea; '),(9846,'for there were neither harbors where ships might ride, nor road-steads, '),(9847,' but projecting headlands, and reefs, and cliffs—'),(9848,'then the knees of Odysseus were loosened and his heart melted, and deeply moved he spoke to his own mighty spirit: '),(9849,' \n“Ah me, when Zeus has at length granted me to see the land beyond my hopes, and lo, I have prevailed to cleave my way and to cross this gulf,  nowhere doth there appear a way to come forth from the grey sea. '),(9850,'For without are sharp