sseus sat him down,'),(10084,'and straightway prayed to the daughter of great Zeus: '),(10085,'“Hear me, child of aegis-bearing Zeus, unwearied one.'),(10086,'Hearken now to my prayer, since aforetime thou didst not hearken when I was smitten, what time the glorious Earth-shaker smote me.'),(10087,'Grant that I may come to the Phaeacians as one to be welcomed and to be pitied.”'),(10088,'So he spoke in prayer, and Pallas Athena heard him;'),(10089,'but she did not yet appear to him face to face,'),(10090,'for she feared  her father\'s brother;'),(10091,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 6.330-631'),(10092,' So he prayed there, the much-enduring goodly Odysseus, while the two strong mules bore the maiden to the city. '),(10093,'But when she had come to the glorious palace of her father, she halted the mules at the outer gate, and her brothers  thronged about her, men like the immortals, and loosed the mules from the wagon, and bore the raiment within; '),(10094,'and she herself went to her chamber.'),(10095,' There a fire was kindled for her by her waiting-woman, Eurymedusa, an aged dame from Apeire. Long ago the curved ships had brought her from Apeire, '),(10096,' and men had chosen her from the spoil as a gift of honor for Alcinous, for that he was king over all the Phaeacians, and the people hearkened to him as to a god.'),(10097,' She it was who had reared the white-armed Nausicaa in the palace,'),(10098,'and she it was who kindled the fire for her, and made ready her supper in the chamber.'),(10099,'\nThen Odysseus roused himself to go to the city,'),(10100,'and Athena,  with kindly purpose, cast about him a thick mist, that no one of the great-hearted Phaeacians, meeting him, should speak mockingly to him, and ask him who he was.'),(10101,' But when he was about to enter the lovely city, then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, met him  in the guise of a young maiden carrying a pitcher, '),(10102,'and she stood before him; and goodly Odysseus questioned her, saying:'),(10103,'\n“My child, couldst thou not guide me to the house of him they call Alcinous, who is lord among the people here?'),(10104,' For I am come hither a stranger sore-tried  from afar, from a distant country; '),(10105,'wherefore I know no one of the people who possess this city and land.\"'),(10106,'Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(10107,' “Then verily, Sir stranger, I will shew thee the palace as thou dost bid me, for it lies hard by the house of my own noble father.'),(10108,'  Only go thou quietly, and I will lead the way.  But turn not thine eyes upon any man nor question any,'),(10109,' for the men here endure not stranger-folk, nor do they give kindly welcome to him who comes from another land.'),(10110,' They, indeed, trusting in the speed of their swift ships,  cross over the great gulf of the sea, for this the Earth-shaker has granted them; '),(10111,'and their ships are swift as a bird on the wing or as a thought.” '),(10112,' \nSo speaking, Pallas Athena led the way quickly, '),(10113,' and he followed in the footsteps of the goddess. '),(10114,' And as he went through the city in the midst of them, the Phaeacians, famed for their ships, took no heed of him, '),(10115,'for fair-tressed Athena, the dread goddess, would not suffer it, but shed about him a wondrous mist, for her heart was kind toward him.'),(10116,' And Odysseus marvelled at the harbors and the stately ships, at the meeting-places where the heroes themselves gathered, and the walls, long and  high and crowned with palisades, a wonder to behold. '),(10117,' But when they had come to the glorious palace of the king, the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, was the first to speak, saying:'),(10118,'“Here, Sir stranger, is the house which thou didst bid me shew to thee,'),(10119,' and thou wilt find the kings, fostered of Zeus,  feasting at the banquet.'),(10120,' Go thou within, and let thy heart fear nothing;'),(10121,' for a bold man is better in all things, though he be a stranger from another land.'),(10122,'The queen shalt thou approach first in the palace;'),(10123,'  Arete is the name by which she is called,  and she is sprung from the same line as is the king Alcinous. '),(10124,'Nausithous at the first was born from the earth-shaker Poseidon and Periboea, the comeliest of women, youngest daughter of great-hearted Eurymedon, who once was king over the insolent Giants.'),(10125,'  But he brought destruction on his froward people, and was himself destroyed.'),(10126,' But with Periboea lay Poseidon and begat a son, great-hearted Nausithous, who ruled over the Phaeacians; '),(10127,'and Nausithous begat Rhexenor and Alcinous.'),(10128,' Rhexenor, when as yet he had no son, Apollo of the silver bow smote  in his hall, a bridegroom though he was, and he left only one daughter, Arete.'),(10129,' Her Alcinous made his wife, and honored her as no other woman on earth is honored, of all those who in these days direct their households in subjection to their husbands;'),(10130,'so heartily is she honored,  and has ever been, by her children and by Alcinous himself and by the people, who look upon her as upon a goddess, and greet her as she goes through the city.'),(10131,'For she of herself is no wise lacking in good understanding,'),(10132,'  and for the women to whom she has good will she makes an end of strife even among their husbands. '),(10133,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 7.75-7.77'),(10134,' \nSo saying, flashing-eyed Athena departed over the unresting sea, and left lovely Scheria.  She came to Marathon and broad-wayed Athens, and entered the well-built house of Erectheus; '),(10135,'but Odysseus went to the glorious palace of Alcinous.'),(10136,' There he stood, and his heart pondered much before he reached the threshold of bronze;'),(10137,'for there was a gleam as of sun or moon  over the high-roofed house of great-hearted Alcinous. '),(10138,'Of bronze were the walls that stretched this way and that from the threshold to the innermost chamber, and around was a cornice of cyanus.'),(10139,' Golden were the doors that shut in the well-built house, '),(10140,'and doorposts of silver were set in a threshold of bronze. Of silver was the lintel above, and of gold the handle.'),(10141,'  On either side of the door there stood gold and silver dogs, which Hephaestus had fashioned with cunning skill to guard the palace of great-hearted Alcinous; immortal were they and ageless all their days.'),(10142,'  Within, seats were fixed along the wall on either hand, from the threshold to the innermost chamber, and on them were thrown robes of soft fabric, cunningly woven, the handiwork of women.'),(10143,' On these the leaders of the Phaeacians were wont to sit drinking and eating,'),(10144,'for they had unfailing store.'),(10145,'  And golden youths stood on well-built pedestals, holding lighted torches in their hands to give light by night to the banqueters in the hall. '),(10146,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 7.103-7.106'),(10147,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 7.107'),(10148,' For as the Phaeacian men are skilled above all others in speeding a swift ship upon the sea, so are the women  cunning workers at the loom, '),(10149,'for Athena has given to them above all others skill in fair handiwork, and an understanding heart.'),(10150,' But without the courtyard, hard by the door, is a great orchard of four acres, '),(10151,' and a hedge runs about it on either side. '),(10152,'Therein grow trees, tall and luxuriant,  pears and pomegranates and apple-trees with their bright fruit, and sweet figs, and luxuriant olives.'),(10153,' Of these the fruit perishes not nor fails in winter or in summer, but lasts throughout the year; '),(10154,'and ever does the west wind, as it blows, quicken to life some fruits, and ripen others; '),(10155,' pear upon pear waxes ripe, apple upon apple, cluster upon cluster, and fig upon fig.'),(10156,' There, too, is his fruitful vineyard planted, one part of which, a warm spot on level ground, is being dried in the sun, while other grapes men are gathering,  and others, too, they are treading; '),(10157,'but in front are unripe grapes that are shedding the blossom, and others that are turning purple.'),(10158,' There again, by the last row of the vines, grow trim garden beds of every sort, blooming the year through, '),(10159,'and therein are two springs, one of which sends its water throughout all the garden,  while the other, over against it, flows beneath the threshold of the court toward the high house; from this the townsfolk drew their water. '),(10160,'Such were the glorious gifts of the gods in the palace of Alcinous.'),(10161,' There the much-enduring goodly Odysseus stood and gazed. '),(10162,'But when he had marvelled in his heart at all things,  he passed quickly over the threshold into the house. '),(10163,'There he found the leaders and counsellors of the Phaeacians pouring libations from their cups to the keen-sighted Argeiphontes, to whom they were wont to pour the wine last of all, when they were minded to go to their rest. '),(10164,'But the much-enduring goodly Odysseus went through the hall,  wrapped in the thick mist which Athena had shed about him, till he came to Arete and to Alcinous the king.'),(10165,' About the knees of Arete Odysseus cast his hands, and straightway the wondrous mist melted from him, '),(10166,' and a hush fell upon all that were in the room at sight of the man, '),(10167,'But Odysseus made his prayer:'),(10168,'But Odysseus made his prayer:'),(10169,'“Arete, daughter of godlike Rhexenor, to thy husband and to thy knees am I come after many toils,—aye and to these banqueters, '),(10170,'to whom may the gods grant happiness in life, and may each of them hand down to his children  the wealth in his halls, and the dues of honor which the people have given him. But for me do ye speed my sending, that I may come to my native land, and that quickly; for long time have I been suffering woes far from my friends.” '),(10171,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 7.151-7.152'),(10172,' \nSo saying he sat down on the hearth in the ashes by the fire, '),(10173,'and they were all hushed in silence.'),(10174,'  But at length there spoke among them the old lord Echeneus, who was an elder among the Phaeacians, well skilled in speech, and understanding all the wisdom of old.'),(10175,' He with good intent addressed the assembly, and said: '),(10176,'“Alcinous, lo, this is not the better way, nor is it seemly,  that a stranger should sit upon the ground on the hearth in the ashes; but these others hold back waiting for thy word.'),(10177,' Come, make the stranger to arise, and set him upon a silver-studded chair, and bid the heralds mix wine,  that we may pour libations also to Zeus, who hurls the thunderbolt; for he ever attends upon reverend suppliants. '),(10178,' And let the housewife give supper to the stranger of the store that is in the house.”'),(10179,'When the strong and mighty Alcinous heard this, he took by the hand Odysseus, the wise and crafty-minded, and raised him from the hearth, and set him upon a bright chair  from which he bade his son, the kindly Laodamas, to rise; for he sat next to him, and was his best beloved.'),(10180,' Then a handmaid brought water for the hands in a fair pitcher of gold, and poured it over a silver basin, for him to wash, '),(10181,'and beside him drew up a polished table.'),(10182,'  And the grave housewife brought and set before him bread, and therewith dainties in abundance, giving freely of her store.'),(10183,' So the much-enduring goodly Odysseus drank and ate; '),(10184,'and then the mighty Alcinous spoke to the herald, and said:'),(10185,'“Pontonous, mix the bowl, and serve wine  to all in the hall, that we may pour libations also to Zeus, who hurls the thunderbolt; for he ever attends upon reverend suppliants.\"'),(10186,'He spoke, and Pontonous mixed the honey-hearted wine, and served out to all, pouring first drops for libation into the cups.'),(10187,' But when they had poured libations, and had drunk to their heart\'s content,  Alcinous addressed the assembly, and spoke among them:'),(10188,'“Hearken to me, leaders and counsellors of the Phaeacians, that I may say what the heart in my breast bids me.'),(10189,' Now that ye have finished your feast, go each of you to his house to rest. '),(10190,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 7.189-7.196'),(10191,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 7.196-7.198'),(10192,' But if he is one of the immortals come down from heaven,  then is this some new thing which the gods are planning; '),(10193,'for ever heretofore have they been wont to appear to us in manifest form, when we sacrifice to them glorious hecatombs, and they feast among us, sitting even where we sit. '),(10194,'Aye, and if one of us as a lone wayfarer meets them,  they use no concealment, for we are of near kin to them, as are the Cyclopes and the wild tribes of the Giants.\"'),(10195,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(10196,' “Alcinous, far from thee be that thought; '),(10197,'for I am not like the immortals, who hold broad heaven,  either in stature or in form, but like mortal men. '),(10198,'Whomsoever ye know among men who bear greatest burden of woe, to them might I liken myself in my sorrows.'),(10199,' Yea, and I could tell a yet longer tale of all the evils which I have endured by the will of the gods.'),(10200,'  But as for me, suffer me now to eat, despite my grief; '),(10201,'for there is nothing more shameless than a hateful belly, which bids a man perforce take thought thereof, be he never so sore distressed and laden with grief at heart, even as I, too, am laden with grief at heart, yet ever does my belly  bid me e